       <a href="/wiki/Australia_(continent)" title="Australia (continent)">
        Australia (continent)

        Oceania (disambiguation)
       </a>

           Associated (2) (

            </span>
            <a href="/wiki/Samoa" title="Samoa">
             Samoa
            </a>
           </li>
           <li style="line-height: inherit; margin: 0">
            <span class="flagicon">
             <img alt="" class="thumbborder" data-file-height="2880" data-file-width="4320" height="15" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/48/Flag_of_Singapore.svg/23px-Flag_of_Singapore.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/48/Flag_of_Singapore.svg/35px-Flag_of_Singapore.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/48/Flag_of_Singapore.svg/45px-Flag_of_Singapore.svg.png 2x" width="23"/>
            </span>
            <a href="/wiki/Singapore" title="Singapore">
             Singapore
            </a>
           </li>
           <li style="line-height: inherit; margin: 0">
            <span class="flagicon">
             <img alt="" class="thumbborder" data-file-height="400" data-file-width="800" height="12" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/74/Flag_of_the_Solomon_Islands.svg/23px-Flag_of_the_Solomon_Islands.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/74/Flag_of_the_Solomon_Islands.svg/35px-Flag_of_the_Solomon_Islands.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/74/Flag_of_the_Solomon_Islands.svg/46px-Flag_of_the_Solomon_Islands.svg.png 2x" width="23"/>
            </span>
            <a href="/wiki/Solomon_Islands" title="Solomon Islands">
             Solomon Islands
            </a>
           </li>
           <li style="line-height: inherit; margin: 0">
            <span class="flagicon">
             <img alt="" class="thumbborder" data-file-height="480" data-file-width="960" height="12" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9a/Flag_of_Tonga.svg/23px-Flag_of_Tonga.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9a/Flag_of_Tonga.svg/35px-Flag_of_Tonga.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9a/Flag_of_Tonga.svg/46px-Flag_of_Tonga.svg.png 2x" width="23"/>
            </span>
            <a href="/wiki/Tonga" title="Tonga">
             Tonga
            </a>
           </li>
           <li style="line-height: inherit; margin: 0">
            <span class="flagicon">
             <img alt="" class="thumbborder" data-file-height="600" data-file-width="1200" height="12" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/38/Flag_of_Tuvalu.svg/23px-Flag_of_Tuvalu.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/38/Flag_of_Tuvalu.svg/35px-Flag_of_Tuvalu.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/38/Flag_of_Tuvalu.svg/46px-Flag_of_Tuvalu.svg.png 2x" width="23"/>
            </span>
            <a href="/wiki/Tuvalu" title="Tuvalu">
             Tuvalu
            </a>
           </li>
           <li style="line-height: inherit; margin: 0">
            <span class="flagicon">
             <img alt="" class="thumbborder" data-file-height="360" data-file-width="600" height="14" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bc/Flag_of_Vanuatu.svg/23px-Flag_of_Vanuatu.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bc/Flag_of_Vanuatu.svg/35px-Flag_of_Vanuatu.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bc/Flag_of_Vanuatu.svg/46px-Flag_of_Vanuatu.svg.png 2x" width="23"/>
            </span>
            <a href="/wiki/Vanuatu" title="Vanuatu">
             Vanuatu
            </a>
           </li>
          </ul>
         </div>
        </td>
       </tr>
      </table>
      <p>
       <b>
        Oceania
       </b>
       (
       <span class="nowrap">
        <small>
         <a href="/wiki/British_English" title="British English">
          UK
         </a>
         :
        </small>
        <span class="IPA nopopups noexcerpt">
         <a href="/wiki/Help:IPA/English" title="Help:IPA/English">
          /
          <span style="border-bottom:1px dotted">
           <span title="/ˌ/: secondary stress follows">
            ˌ
           </span>
           <span title="/oʊ/: 'o' in 'code'">
            oʊ
           </span>
           <span title="/ʃ/: 'sh' in 'shy'">
            ʃ
           </span>
           <span title="/i/: 'y' in 'happy'">
            i
           </span>
           <span title="/ˈ/: primary stress follows">
            ˈ
           </span>
           <span title="/ɑː/: 'a' in 'father'">
            ɑː
           </span>
           <span title="'n' in 'nigh'">
            n
           </span>
           <span title="/i/: 'y' in 'happy'">
            i
           </span>
           <span title="/ə/: 'a' in 'about'">
            ə
           </span>
          </span>
          ,
          <span style="border-bottom:1px dotted">
           <span title="/ˌ/: secondary stress follows">
            ˌ
           </span>
           <span title="/oʊ/: 'o' in 'code'">
            oʊ
           </span>
           <span title="'s' in 'sigh'">
            s
           </span>
           <span title="/i/: 'y' in 'happy'">
            i
           </span>
          </span>
          -/
         </a>
        </span>
       </span>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-OED_Oceania_3-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-OED_Oceania-3">
         [3]
        </a>
       </sup>
       or
       <span class="nowrap">
        <small>
         <a href="/wiki/American_English" title="American English">
          US
         </a>
         :
        </small>
        <span class="IPA nopopups noexcerpt">
         <a href="/wiki/Help:IPA/English" title="Help:IPA/English">
          /
          <span style="border-bottom:1px dotted">
           <span title="/ˌ/: secondary stress follows">
            ˌ
           </span>
           <span title="/oʊ/: 'o' in 'code'">
            oʊ
           </span>
           <span title="/ʃ/: 'sh' in 'shy'">
            ʃ
           </span>
           <span title="/iː/: 'ee' in 'fleece'">
            iː
           </span>
           <span title="/ˈ/: primary stress follows">
            ˈ
           </span>
           <span title="/æ/: 'a' in 'bad'">
            æ
           </span>
           <span title="'n' in 'nigh'">
            n
           </span>
           <span title="/i/: 'y' in 'happy'">
            i
           </span>
           <span title="/ə/: 'a' in 'about'">
            ə
           </span>
          </span>
          /
         </a>
        </span>
       </span>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-4">
        <a href="#cite_note-4">
         [4]
        </a>
       </sup>
       ) is a geographic region comprising
       <a href="/wiki/Melanesia" title="Melanesia">
        Melanesia
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Micronesia" title="Micronesia">
        Micronesia
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Polynesia" title="Polynesia">
        Polynesia
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Australasia" title="Australasia">
        Australasia
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-5">
        <a href="#cite_note-5">
         [5]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Spanning the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Eastern_hemisphere" title="Eastern hemisphere">
        eastern
       </a>
       and
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Western_hemisphere" title="Western hemisphere">
        western hemispheres
       </a>
       , Oceania covers an area of 8,525,989 square kilometres (3,291,903 sq mi) and has a population of 40 million. Situated in the southeast of the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Asia_Pacific" title="Asia Pacific">
        Asia Pacific
       </a>
       region, Oceania is the smallest continental grouping in
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Land_area" title="Land area">
        land area
       </a>
       and the second
       <a href="/wiki/List_of_continents_by_population" title="List of continents by population">
        smallest in population
       </a>
       after
       <a href="/wiki/Antarctica" title="Antarctica">
        Antarctica
       </a>
       .
      </p>
      <p>
       The islands at the geographic extremes of Oceania are
       <a href="/wiki/Bonin_Islands" title="Bonin Islands">
        Bonin Islands
       </a>
       , a politically integral part of
       <a href="/wiki/Japan" title="Japan">
        Japan
       </a>
       ;
       <a href="/wiki/Hawaii" title="Hawaii">
        Hawaii
       </a>
       , a state of the
       <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">
        United States
       </a>
       ;
       <a href="/wiki/Clipperton_Island" title="Clipperton Island">
        Clipperton Island
       </a>
       , a possession of France; the
       <a href="/wiki/Juan_Fern%C3%A1ndez_Islands" title="Juan Fernández Islands">
        Juan Fernández Islands
       </a>
       , belonging to
       <a href="/wiki/Chile" title="Chile">
        Chile
       </a>
       ; the
       <a href="/wiki/Campbell_Islands" title="Campbell Islands">
        Campbell Islands
       </a>
       , belonging to New Zealand; and the
       <a href="/wiki/Cocos_(Keeling)_Islands" title="Cocos (Keeling) Islands">
        Cocos (Keeling) Islands
       </a>
       , belonging to Australia. Oceania has a diverse mix of economies from the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Developed_countries" title="Developed countries">
        highly developed
       </a>
       and globally competitive
       <a href="/wiki/Market_economy" title="Market economy">
        financial market
       </a>
       of Australia and New Zealand, which rank high in
       <a href="/wiki/Quality_of_life" title="Quality of life">
        quality of life
       </a>
       and
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Human_development_index" title="Human development index">
        human development index
       </a>
       ,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-6">
        <a href="#cite_note-6">
         [6]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-7">
        <a href="#cite_note-7">
         [7]
        </a>
       </sup>
       to the much
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Least_developed_countries" title="Least developed countries">
        less developed economies
       </a>
       that belong to countries such as of
       <a href="/wiki/Kiribati" title="Kiribati">
        Kiribati
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Tuvalu" title="Tuvalu">
        Tuvalu
       </a>
       ,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-8">
        <a href="#cite_note-8">
         [8]
        </a>
       </sup>
       while also including
       <a href="/wiki/Developing_country" title="Developing country">
        medium-sized economies
       </a>
       of pacific islands such as
       <a href="/wiki/Palau" title="Palau">
        Palau
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Fiji" title="Fiji">
        Fiji
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Tonga" title="Tonga">
        Tonga
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-9">
        <a href="#cite_note-9">
         [9]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The largest and most populous
       <a href="/wiki/List_of_sovereign_states_and_dependent_territories_in_Oceania" title="List of sovereign states and dependent territories in Oceania">
        country in Oceania
       </a>
       is Australia, with
       <a href="/wiki/Sydney" title="Sydney">
        Sydney
       </a>
       being the largest city of both Oceania and Australia.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-10">
        <a href="#cite_note-10">
         [10]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       The first settlers of Australia, New Guinea, and the large islands just to the east arrived between
       <a href="/wiki/Upper_Paleolithic" title="Upper Paleolithic">
        50,000 and 30,000 years ago
       </a>
       . Oceania was
       <a href="/wiki/Exploration_of_the_Pacific" title="Exploration of the Pacific">
        first explored by Europeans
       </a>
       from the 16th century onward.
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Portuguese_navigators" title="Portuguese navigators">
        Portuguese navigators
       </a>
       , between 1512 and 1526, reached the
       <a href="/wiki/Tanimbar_Islands" title="Tanimbar Islands">
        Tanimbar Islands
       </a>
       , some of the
       <a href="/wiki/Caroline_Islands" title="Caroline Islands">
        Caroline Islands
       </a>
       and west
       <a href="/wiki/Papua_New_Guinea" title="Papua New Guinea">
        Papua New Guinea
       </a>
       . On his first voyage in the 18th century,
       <a href="/wiki/James_Cook" title="James Cook">
        James Cook
       </a>
       , who later founded the
       <a href="/wiki/Hawaiian_Islands" title="Hawaiian Islands">
        Hawaiian Islands
       </a>
       , went to
       <a href="/wiki/Tahiti" title="Tahiti">
        Tahiti
       </a>
       and followed the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Eastern_Australia" title="Eastern Australia">
        east coast of Australia
       </a>
       for the first time. The
       <a href="/wiki/Military_history_of_Oceania#World_War_II" title="Military history of Oceania">
        Pacific front
       </a>
       saw major action during the
       <a href="/wiki/World_War_II" title="World War II">
        Second World War
       </a>
       , mainly between the belligerents the
       <a href="/wiki/United_States_home_front_during_World_War_II" title="United States home front during World War II">
        United States
       </a>
       , its ally
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Australia_in_World_War_II" title="Australia in World War II">
        Australia
       </a>
       , and
       <a href="/wiki/Empire_of_Japan" title="Empire of Japan">
        Japan
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-11">
        <a href="#cite_note-11">
         [11]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       The
       <a href="/wiki/Europeans_in_Oceania" title="Europeans in Oceania">
        arrival of European settlers
       </a>
       in subsequent centuries resulted in a significant alteration in the social and political landscape of Oceania. In more
       <a href="/wiki/Modern_history" title="Modern history">
        contemporary times
       </a>
       there has been increasing discussion on
       <a href="/wiki/Flags_of_Oceania" title="Flags of Oceania">
        national flags
       </a>
       and a desire by some Oceanians to display their distinguishable and individualistic
       <a href="/wiki/National_identity" title="National identity">
        identity
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-12">
        <a href="#cite_note-12">
         [12]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The
       <a href="/wiki/Rock_art" title="Rock art">
        rock art
       </a>
       of
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Australian_Aborigines" title="Australian Aborigines">
        Australian Aborigines
       </a>
       is the longest continuously practiced artistic tradition in the world.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-13">
        <a href="#cite_note-13">
         [13]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Puncak_Jaya" title="Puncak Jaya">
        Puncak Jaya
       </a>
       in Papua is often considered the highest peak in Oceania.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-14">
        <a href="#cite_note-14">
         [14]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Most Oceanian countries have a
       <a href="/wiki/Parliamentary_system" title="Parliamentary system">
        parliamentary
       </a>
       <a href="/wiki/Representative_democracy" title="Representative democracy">
        representative democratic
       </a>
       <a href="/wiki/Multi-party_system" title="Multi-party system">
        multi-party system
       </a>
       , with
       <a href="/wiki/Tourism" title="Tourism">
        tourism
       </a>
       being a large source of income for the
       <a href="/wiki/Pacific_Islands" title="Pacific Islands">
        Pacific Islands
       </a>
       nations.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-15">
        <a href="#cite_note-15">
         [15]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
      </p>

           </a>
          </li>
          <li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-28">
           <a href="#Pacific_Islands_2">
            <span class="tocnumber">
             6.3
            </span>
            <span class="toctext">
             Pacific Islands
            </span>
           </a>
          </li>
         </ul>
        </li>
        <li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-29">
         <a href="#Culture">
          <span class="tocnumber">
           7
          </span>
          <span class="toctext">
           Culture
          </span>
         </a>
         <ul>
          <li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-30">

            </span>
           </a>
          </li>
          <li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-31">

            </span>
           </a>
          </li>
          <li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-32">

            </span>
           </a>
          </li>
          <li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-33">

            </span>
           </a>
          </li>
          <li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-34">

            </span>
           </a>
          </li>
          <li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-35">

            </span>
           </a>
          </li>
         </ul>
        </li>
        <li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-36">

      <p>
      </p>
      <h2>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Definitions">
        Definitions
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Definitions">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h2>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:302px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Oceania_UN_Geoscheme_Regions.svg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="520" data-file-width="900" height="173" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/54/Oceania_UN_Geoscheme_Regions.svg/300px-Oceania_UN_Geoscheme_Regions.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/54/Oceania_UN_Geoscheme_Regions.svg/450px-Oceania_UN_Geoscheme_Regions.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/54/Oceania_UN_Geoscheme_Regions.svg/600px-Oceania_UN_Geoscheme_Regions.svg.png 2x" width="300"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Oceania_UN_Geoscheme_Regions.svg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         Regions of Oceania
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       The term was coined as
       <i>
        Océanie
       </i>
       circa 1812 by geographer
       <a href="/wiki/Conrad_Malte-Brun" title="Conrad Malte-Brun">
        Conrad Malte-Brun
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-OED_16-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-OED-16">
         [16]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The word
       <i>
        Océanie
       </i>
       is a
       <a href="/wiki/French_language" title="French language">
        French
       </a>
       word derived from the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Latin_language" title="Latin language">
        Latin
       </a>
       word
       <i lang="la" xml:lang="la">
        <a class="extiw" href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/oceanus#Latin" title="wikt:oceanus">
         oceanus
        </a>
       </i>
       , and this from the
       <a href="/wiki/Greek_language" title="Greek language">
        Greek
       </a>
       word
       <span lang="grc" xml:lang="grc">
        <a class="extiw" href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E1%BD%A0%CE%BA%CE%B5%CE%B1%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%82#Ancient_Greek" title="wikt:ὠκεανός">
         ὠκεανός
        </a>
       </span>
       (
       <i>
        ōkeanós
       </i>
       ), ocean. Natives and inhabitants of this region are called Oceanians or Oceanicans.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-17">
        <a href="#cite_note-17">
         [17]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The term
       <i>
        Oceania
       </i>
       is used because, unlike the other continental groupings, it is the ocean that links the nations together.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-18">
        <a href="#cite_note-18">
         [18]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <ul>
       <li>
        Biogeographically, as a synonym for the
        <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Australasian_ecozone" title="Australasian ecozone">
         Australasian ecozone
        </a>
        and the Pacific ecozone (Melanesia, Polynesia, and Micronesia), with New Zealand forming the south-western corner of the
        <a href="/wiki/Polynesian_Triangle" title="Polynesian Triangle">
         Polynesian Triangle
        </a>
        . To note, New Zealand may also be considered part of Australasia, despite being traditionally part of Polynesia.
        <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Udvardy_1975_19-0">
         <a href="#cite_note-Udvardy_1975-19">
          [19]
         </a>
        </sup>
       </li>
       <li>
        As an
        <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Ecozone" title="Ecozone">
         ecozone
        </a>
        ,
        <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Oceania_Ecozone" title="Oceania Ecozone">
         Oceania
        </a>
        includes all of
        <a href="/wiki/Micronesia" title="Micronesia">
         Micronesia
        </a>
        ,
        <a href="/wiki/Fiji" title="Fiji">
         Fiji
        </a>
        , and all of Polynesia except New Zealand. New Zealand, along with
        <a href="/wiki/New_Guinea" title="New Guinea">
         New Guinea
        </a>
        and nearby islands, part of the
        <a href="/wiki/Philippines" title="Philippines">
         Philippine islands
        </a>
        ,
        <a href="/wiki/Australia" title="Australia">
         Australia
        </a>
        , the
        <a href="/wiki/Solomon_Islands" title="Solomon Islands">
         Solomon Islands
        </a>
        ,
        <a href="/wiki/Vanuatu" title="Vanuatu">
         Vanuatu
        </a>
        , and
        <a href="/wiki/New_Caledonia" title="New Caledonia">
         New Caledonia
        </a>
        , constitute the separate
        <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Australasian_ecozone" title="Australasian ecozone">
         Australasian ecozone
        </a>
        .
        <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Philip's_E.A.E.P_Atlas_20-0">
         <a href="#cite_note-Philip's_E.A.E.P_Atlas-20">
          [20]
         </a>
        </sup>
       </li>
       <li>
        In the geopolitical conception used by the
        <a href="/wiki/United_Nations_geoscheme" title="United Nations geoscheme">
         United Nations
        </a>
        ,
        <a href="/wiki/International_Olympic_Committee" title="International Olympic Committee">
         International Olympic Committee
        </a>
        , and many atlases, Oceania includes
        <a href="/wiki/Australia" title="Australia">
         Australia
        </a>
        and the nations of the Pacific from Papua New Guinea east, but not the
        <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Indonesian_New_Guinea" title="Indonesian New Guinea">
         Indonesian New Guinea
        </a>
        .
        <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Lewis_1997_32_21-0">
         <a href="#cite_note-Lewis_1997_32-21">
          [21]
         </a>
        </sup>
       </li>
      </ul>
      <h2>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="History">
        History
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: History">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h2>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       Main article:
       <a href="/wiki/History_of_Oceania" title="History of Oceania">
        History of Oceania
       </a>
      </div>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Australia">
        Australia
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Australia">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       Main articles:
       <a href="/wiki/Prehistory_of_Australia" title="Prehistory of Australia">
        Prehistory of Australia
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/History_of_Indigenous_Australians" title="History of Indigenous Australians">
        History of Indigenous Australians
       </a>
      </div>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:262px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Native_Encampment_by_Skinner_Prout,_from_Australia_(1876,_vol_II).jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="715" data-file-width="1363" height="136" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fc/Native_Encampment_by_Skinner_Prout%2C_from_Australia_%281876%2C_vol_II%29.jpg/260px-Native_Encampment_by_Skinner_Prout%2C_from_Australia_%281876%2C_vol_II%29.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fc/Native_Encampment_by_Skinner_Prout%2C_from_Australia_%281876%2C_vol_II%29.jpg/390px-Native_Encampment_by_Skinner_Prout%2C_from_Australia_%281876%2C_vol_II%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fc/Native_Encampment_by_Skinner_Prout%2C_from_Australia_%281876%2C_vol_II%29.jpg/520px-Native_Encampment_by_Skinner_Prout%2C_from_Australia_%281876%2C_vol_II%29.jpg 2x" width="260"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Native_Encampment_by_Skinner_Prout,_from_Australia_(1876,_vol_II).jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         A 19th-century engraving of an Aboriginal Australian encampment.
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       <a href="/wiki/Indigenous_Australians" title="Indigenous Australians">
        Indigenous Australians
       </a>
       are the original inhabitants of the
       <a href="/wiki/Australia_(continent)" title="Australia (continent)">
        Australian continent
       </a>
       and nearby islands who migrated from Africa to Asia around 70,000 years ago
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-22">
        <a href="#cite_note-22">
         [22]
        </a>
       </sup>
       and arrived in Australia around 50,000 years ago.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-illumina.com_23-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-illumina.com-23">
         [23]
        </a>
       </sup>
       They are believed to be among the
       <a href="/wiki/Recent_African_origin_of_modern_humans" title="Recent African origin of modern humans">
        earliest human migrations out of Africa
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-BBSRC_24-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-BBSRC-24">
         [24]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Although they likely migrated to Australia through
       <a href="/wiki/Southeast_Asia" title="Southeast Asia">
        Southeast Asia
       </a>
       they are not demonstrably related to any known Asian or
       <a href="/wiki/Polynesia" title="Polynesia">
        Polynesian
       </a>
       population.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-25">
        <a href="#cite_note-25">
         [25]
        </a>
       </sup>
       There is evidence of genetic and linguistic interchange between Australians in the far north and the Austronesian peoples of modern-day
       <a href="/wiki/New_Guinea" title="New Guinea">
        New Guinea
       </a>
       and the islands, but this may be the result of recent trade and
       <a href="/wiki/Interracial_marriage" title="Interracial marriage">
        intermarriage
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-26">
        <a href="#cite_note-26">
         [26]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       They reached
       <a href="/wiki/Tasmania" title="Tasmania">
        Tasmania
       </a>
       approximately 40,000 years ago by migrating across a
       <a href="/wiki/Land_bridge" title="Land bridge">
        land bridge
       </a>
       from the mainland that existed during the last
       <a href="/wiki/Ice_age" title="Ice age">
        ice age
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-27">
        <a href="#cite_note-27">
         [27]
        </a>
       </sup>
       It is believed that the first
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Early_human_migration" title="Early human migration">
        early human migration
       </a>
       to Australia was achieved when this landmass formed part of the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Sahul_continent" title="Sahul continent">
        Sahul continent
       </a>
       , connected to the island of New Guinea via a land bridge.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-28">
        <a href="#cite_note-28">
         [28]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The
       <a href="/wiki/Torres_Strait_Islanders" title="Torres Strait Islanders">
        Torres Strait Islanders
       </a>
       are indigenous to the
       <a href="/wiki/Torres_Strait" title="Torres Strait">
        Torres Strait
       </a>
       Islands, which are at the northernmost tip of Queensland near
       <a href="/wiki/Papua_New_Guinea" title="Papua New Guinea">
        Papua New Guinea
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-uow2004_29-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-uow2004-29">
         [29]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The earliest definite human remains found in Australia are that of
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Mungo_Man" title="Mungo Man">
        Mungo Man
       </a>
       , which have been dated at about 40,000 years old.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-pmid4570638_30-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-pmid4570638-30">
         [30]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Melanesia">
        Melanesia
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Melanesia">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:262px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Melanesians.jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="402" data-file-width="824" height="127" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/84/Melanesians.jpg/260px-Melanesians.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/84/Melanesians.jpg/390px-Melanesians.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/84/Melanesians.jpg/520px-Melanesians.jpg 2x" width="260"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Melanesians.jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         Distribution of Melanesians
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       Main article:
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/History_of_New_Guinea" title="History of New Guinea">
        History of New Guinea
       </a>
      </div>
      <p>
       The original inhabitants of the group of islands now named Melanesia were likely the ancestors of the present-day
       <a href="/wiki/Papuan_languages" title="Papuan languages">
        Papuan
       </a>
       -speaking people. Migrating from South-East Asia, they appear to have occupied these islands as far east as the main islands in the
       <a href="/wiki/Solomon_Islands" title="Solomon Islands">
        Solomon Islands
       </a>
       , including
       <a href="/wiki/Makira" title="Makira">
        Makira
       </a>
       and possibly the smaller islands farther to the east.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-31">
        <a href="#cite_note-31">
         [31]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       Particularly along the north coast of New Guinea and in the islands north and east of New Guinea, the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Austronesian_people" title="Austronesian people">
        Austronesian people
       </a>
       , who had migrated into the area somewhat more than 3,000 years ago, came into contact with these pre-existing populations of Papuan-speaking peoples. In the late 20th century, some scholars theorized a long period of interaction, which resulted in many complex changes in genetics, languages, and culture among the peoples.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-32">
        <a href="#cite_note-32">
         [32]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Polynesia">
        Polynesia
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Polynesia">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       Main articles:
       <a href="/wiki/History_of_Hawaii" title="History of Hawaii">
        History of Hawaii
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/History_of_New_Zealand" title="History of New Zealand">
        History of New Zealand
       </a>
      </div>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:AhuTongariki.jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="1026" data-file-width="1496" height="151" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/14/AhuTongariki.jpg/220px-AhuTongariki.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/14/AhuTongariki.jpg/330px-AhuTongariki.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/14/AhuTongariki.jpg/440px-AhuTongariki.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:AhuTongariki.jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         <a href="/wiki/Moai" title="Moai">
          Moai
         </a>
         at Ahu Tongariki on
         <a href="/wiki/Easter_Island" title="Easter Island">
          Rapa Nui (Easter Island)
         </a>
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       The Polynesian people are considered to be by linguistic, archaeological and human genetic ancestry a subset of the sea-migrating
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Austronesian_people" title="Austronesian people">
        Austronesian people
       </a>
       and tracing
       <a href="/wiki/Polynesian_languages" title="Polynesian languages">
        Polynesian languages
       </a>
       places their
       <a href="/wiki/Prehistory" title="Prehistory">
        prehistoric
       </a>
       origins in the
       <a href="/wiki/Malay_Archipelago" title="Malay Archipelago">
        Malay Archipelago
       </a>
       , and ultimately, in
       <a href="/wiki/Geography_of_Taiwan" title="Geography of Taiwan">
        Taiwan
       </a>
       . Between about 3000 and 1000 BC speakers of
       <a href="/wiki/Austronesian_languages" title="Austronesian languages">
        Austronesian languages
       </a>
       began spreading from Taiwan into
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Island_Southeast_Asia" title="Island Southeast Asia">
        Island South-East Asia
       </a>
       ,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-matrilineality2003_33-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-matrilineality2003-33">
         [33]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Kayser,_M._2006_34-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-Kayser,_M._2006-34">
         [34]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-35">
        <a href="#cite_note-35">
         [35]
        </a>
       </sup>
       as tribes whose
       <a href="/wiki/Taiwanese_aborigines" title="Taiwanese aborigines">
        natives
       </a>
       were thought to have arrived through South China about 8,000 years ago to the edges of western
       <a href="/wiki/Micronesia" title="Micronesia">
        Micronesia
       </a>
       and on into
       <a href="/wiki/Melanesia" title="Melanesia">
        Melanesia
       </a>
       .
      </p>
      <p>
       In the archaeological record there are well-defined traces of this expansion which allow the path it took to be followed and dated with some certainty. It is thought that by roughly 1400 BC,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-36">
        <a href="#cite_note-36">
         [36]
        </a>
       </sup>
       "
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Lapita" title="Lapita">
        Lapita
       </a>
       Peoples", so-named after their pottery tradition, appeared in the
       <a href="/wiki/Bismarck_Archipelago" title="Bismarck Archipelago">
        Bismarck Archipelago
       </a>
       of north-west
       <a href="/wiki/Melanesia" title="Melanesia">
        Melanesia
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-test_37-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-test-37">
         [37]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-burley128_38-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-burley128-38">
         [38]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       Easter Islanders claimed that a chief
       <a href="/wiki/Hotu_Matu%27a" title="Hotu Matu'a">
        Hotu Matu'a
       </a>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-39">
        <a href="#cite_note-39">
         [39]
        </a>
       </sup>
       arrived on the island in one or two large canoes with his wife and extended family.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-40">
        <a href="#cite_note-40">
         [40]
        </a>
       </sup>
       They are believed to have been
       <a href="/wiki/Polynesians" title="Polynesians">
        Polynesian
       </a>
       . Published literature suggests the island was settled around AD 300–400, or at about the time of the arrival of the earliest settlers in
       <a href="/wiki/Hawaii" title="Hawaii">
        Hawaii
       </a>
       . Around 1200,
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Tahitian_people" title="Tahitian people">
        Tahitian
       </a>
       explorers found and began settling the area. This date range is based on
       <a href="/wiki/Glottochronology" title="Glottochronology">
        glottochronological
       </a>
       calculations and on three
       <a href="/wiki/Radiocarbon_dating" title="Radiocarbon dating">
        radiocarbon dates
       </a>
       from charcoal that appears to have been produced during forest clearance activities.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-41">
        <a href="#cite_note-41">
         [41]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Moreover, a recent study which included radiocarbon dates from what is thought to be very early material suggests that the island was settled as recently as 1200.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-42">
        <a href="#cite_note-42">
         [42]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Micronesia">
        Micronesia
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Micronesia">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       See also:
       <a href="/wiki/History_of_the_Federated_States_of_Micronesia" title="History of the Federated States of Micronesia">
        History of the Federated States of Micronesia
       </a>
      </div>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:HH1883_pg125_Hafen_von_Jap.jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="2191" data-file-width="2898" height="166" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/HH1883_pg125_Hafen_von_Jap.jpg/220px-HH1883_pg125_Hafen_von_Jap.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/HH1883_pg125_Hafen_von_Jap.jpg/330px-HH1883_pg125_Hafen_von_Jap.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/HH1883_pg125_Hafen_von_Jap.jpg/440px-HH1883_pg125_Hafen_von_Jap.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:HH1883_pg125_Hafen_von_Jap.jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         Stone money transport to
         <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Yap_Island" title="Yap Island">
          Yap Island
         </a>
         in
         <a href="/wiki/Micronesia" title="Micronesia">
          Micronesia
         </a>
         (1880).
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       Micronesia began to be settled several millennia ago, although there are competing theories about the origin and arrival of the first settlers. There are numerous difficulties with conducting archaeological excavations in the islands, due to their size, settlement patterns and storm damage. As a result, much evidence is based on linguistic analysis.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-43">
        <a href="#cite_note-43">
         [43]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       The earliest archaeological traces of civilization have been found on the island of
       <a href="/wiki/Saipan" title="Saipan">
        Saipan
       </a>
       , dated to 1500 BC or slightly before. The ancestors of the Micronesians settled there over 4,000 years ago. A decentralized chieftain-based system eventually evolved into a more centralized economic and religious culture centered on
       <a href="/wiki/Yap" title="Yap">
        Yap
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Pohnpei" title="Pohnpei">
        Pohnpei
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-USDOS_44-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-USDOS-44">
         [44]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The prehistory of many Micronesian islands such as Yap are not known very well.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-books.google_45-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-books.google-45">
         [45]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       The first people of the Northern Mariana Islands navigated to the islands at some period between 4000 B.C. to 2000 B.C. from
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/South-East_Asia" title="South-East Asia">
        South-East Asia
       </a>
       . They became known as the
       <a href="/wiki/Chamorro_people" title="Chamorro people">
        Chamorros
       </a>
       , and spoke an
       <a href="/wiki/Austronesian_languages" title="Austronesian languages">
        Austronesian language
       </a>
       called
       <a href="/wiki/Chamorro_language" title="Chamorro language">
        Chamorro
       </a>
       . The ancient Chamorro left a number of megalithic ruins, including
       <a href="/wiki/Latte_stone" title="Latte stone">
        Latte stone
       </a>
       . The Refaluwasch, or Carolinian, people came to the Marianas in the 1800s from the
       <a href="/wiki/Caroline_Islands" title="Caroline Islands">
        Caroline Islands
       </a>
       . Micronesian colonists gradually settled the Marshall Islands during the
       <a href="/wiki/2nd_millennium_BC" title="2nd millennium BC">
        2nd millennium BC
       </a>
       , with inter-island navigation made possible using
       <a href="/wiki/Marshall_Islands_stick_chart" title="Marshall Islands stick chart">
        traditional stick charts
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-46">
        <a href="#cite_note-46">
         [46]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="European_exploration">
        European exploration
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: European exploration">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       See also:
       <a href="/wiki/Magellan%E2%80%93Elcano_circumnavigation" title="Magellan–Elcano circumnavigation">
        Magellan–Elcano circumnavigation
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Spanish_East_Indies" title="Spanish East Indies">
        Spanish East Indies
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/History_of_Australia_(1788%E2%80%931850)" title="History of Australia (1788–1850)">
        History of Australia (1788–1850)
       </a>
       , and
       <a href="/wiki/Colony_of_New_Zealand" title="Colony of New Zealand">
        Colony of New Zealand
       </a>
      </div>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:1852_Bocage_Map_of_Australia_and_Polynesia_-_Geographicus_-_Oceanie-bocage-1852.jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="2210" data-file-width="3000" height="162" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a2/1852_Bocage_Map_of_Australia_and_Polynesia_-_Geographicus_-_Oceanie-bocage-1852.jpg/220px-1852_Bocage_Map_of_Australia_and_Polynesia_-_Geographicus_-_Oceanie-bocage-1852.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a2/1852_Bocage_Map_of_Australia_and_Polynesia_-_Geographicus_-_Oceanie-bocage-1852.jpg/330px-1852_Bocage_Map_of_Australia_and_Polynesia_-_Geographicus_-_Oceanie-bocage-1852.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a2/1852_Bocage_Map_of_Australia_and_Polynesia_-_Geographicus_-_Oceanie-bocage-1852.jpg/440px-1852_Bocage_Map_of_Australia_and_Polynesia_-_Geographicus_-_Oceanie-bocage-1852.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:1852_Bocage_Map_of_Australia_and_Polynesia_-_Geographicus_-_Oceanie-bocage-1852.jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         1852 map of Oceania by J. G. Barbie du Bocage. Includes regions of Polynesia, Micronesia, Melanesia and Malaysia.
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       From 1527 to 1595 a number of other large Spanish expeditions crossed the
       <a href="/wiki/Pacific_Ocean" title="Pacific Ocean">
        Pacific Ocean
       </a>
       , leading to the discovery of the
       <a href="/wiki/Marshall_Islands" title="Marshall Islands">
        Marshall Islands
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Palau" title="Palau">
        Palau
       </a>
       in the North Pacific, as well as
       <a href="/wiki/Tuvalu" title="Tuvalu">
        Tuvalu
       </a>
       , the
       <a href="/wiki/Marquesas_Islands" title="Marquesas Islands">
        Marquesas
       </a>
       , the
       <a href="/wiki/Solomon_Islands" title="Solomon Islands">
        Solomon Islands
       </a>
       , the
       <a href="/wiki/Cook_Islands" title="Cook Islands">
        Cook Islands
       </a>
       and the
       <a href="/wiki/Admiralty_Islands" title="Admiralty Islands">
        Admiralty Islands
       </a>
       in the South Pacific.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Fernandez-Armesto_2006_305–307_47-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-Fernandez-Armesto_2006_305–307-47">
         [47]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       In the quest for
       <a href="/wiki/Terra_Australis" title="Terra Australis">
        Terra Australis
       </a>
       , Spanish explorations in the 17th century, such as the expedition led by the Portuguese navigator
       <a href="/wiki/Pedro_Fernandes_de_Queir%C3%B3s" title="Pedro Fernandes de Queirós">
        Pedro Fernandes de Queirós
       </a>
       , discovered the
       <a href="/wiki/Pitcairn_Islands" title="Pitcairn Islands">
        Pitcairn
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Vanuatu" title="Vanuatu">
        Vanuatu
       </a>
       archipelagos, and sailed the
       <a href="/wiki/Torres_Strait" title="Torres Strait">
        Torres Strait
       </a>
       between
       <a href="/wiki/Australia" title="Australia">
        Australia
       </a>
       and New Guinea, named after navigator
       <a href="/wiki/Lu%C3%ADs_Vaz_de_Torres" title="Luís Vaz de Torres">
        Luís Vaz de Torres
       </a>
       .
       <a href="/wiki/Willem_Janszoon" title="Willem Janszoon">
        Willem Janszoon
       </a>
       , made the first completely documented European landing in Australia (1606), in
       <a href="/wiki/Cape_York_Peninsula" title="Cape York Peninsula">
        Cape York Peninsula
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-48">
        <a href="#cite_note-48">
         [48]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Abel_Tasman" title="Abel Tasman">
        Abel Janszoon Tasman
       </a>
       circumnavigated and landed on parts of the
       <a href="/wiki/Australia" title="Australia">
        Australian
       </a>
       continental coast and discovered
       <a href="/wiki/Van_Diemen%27s_Land" title="Van Diemen's Land">
        Van Diemen's Land
       </a>
       (now
       <a href="/wiki/Tasmania" title="Tasmania">
        Tasmania
       </a>
       ),
       <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand" title="New Zealand">
        New Zealand
       </a>
       in 1642, and
       <a href="/wiki/Fiji" title="Fiji">
        Fiji
       </a>
       islands.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-49">
        <a href="#cite_note-49">
         [49]
        </a>
       </sup>
       He was the first known European explorer to reach these islands.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-50">
        <a href="#cite_note-50">
         [50]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       On 23 April 1770 British explorer
       <a href="/wiki/James_Cook" title="James Cook">
        James Cook
       </a>
       made his first recorded direct observation of
       <a href="/wiki/Indigenous_Australians" title="Indigenous Australians">
        indigenous Australians
       </a>
       at
       <a href="/wiki/Brush_Island" title="Brush Island">
        Brush Island
       </a>
       near
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Bawley_Point,_New_South_Wales" title="Bawley Point, New South Wales">
        Bawley Point
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-51">
        <a href="#cite_note-51">
         [51]
        </a>
       </sup>
       On 29 April, Cook and crew made their first landfall on the mainland of the continent at a place now known as the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Cronulla_sand_dunes,_Kurnell_Peninsula" title="Cronulla sand dunes, Kurnell Peninsula">
        Kurnell Peninsula
       </a>
       . It is here that James Cook made first contact with an aboriginal tribe known as the
       <a href="/wiki/Gweagal" title="Gweagal">
        Gweagal
       </a>
       . His expedition became the first recorded Europeans to have encountered its eastern coastline of Australia.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-52">
        <a href="#cite_note-52">
         [52]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h4>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Colonization">
        Colonization
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Colonization">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h4>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       See also:
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Colonisation_of_Australia" title="Colonisation of Australia">
        Colonisation of Australia
       </a>
       and
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Colonisation_of_New_Zealand" title="Colonisation of New Zealand">
        Colonisation of New Zealand
       </a>
      </div>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:New_Guinea_(1884-1919).png">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="319" data-file-width="618" height="114" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/ba/New_Guinea_%281884-1919%29.png/220px-New_Guinea_%281884-1919%29.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/ba/New_Guinea_%281884-1919%29.png/330px-New_Guinea_%281884-1919%29.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/ba/New_Guinea_%281884-1919%29.png/440px-New_Guinea_%281884-1919%29.png 2x" width="220"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:New_Guinea_(1884-1919).png" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         New Guinea from 1884 to 1919.
         <a href="/wiki/Netherlands" title="Netherlands">
          The Netherlands
         </a>
         controlled the western half of New Guinea,
         <a href="/wiki/German_Empire" title="German Empire">
          Germany
         </a>
         the north-eastern part, and
         <a href="/wiki/United_Kingdom_of_Great_Britain_and_Ireland" title="United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland">
          Britain
         </a>
         the south-eastern part.
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       In 1789 the
       <a href="/wiki/Mutiny_on_the_Bounty" title="Mutiny on the Bounty">
        Mutiny on the Bounty
       </a>
       against
       <a href="/wiki/William_Bligh" title="William Bligh">
        William Bligh
       </a>
       led to several of the mutineers escaping the
       <a href="/wiki/Royal_Navy" title="Royal Navy">
        Royal Navy
       </a>
       and settling on
       <a href="/wiki/Pitcairn_Islands" title="Pitcairn Islands">
        Pitcairn Islands
       </a>
       , which later became a British colony. Britain also established colonies in Australia in 1788, New Zealand in 1840 and
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Colonial_Fiji" title="Colonial Fiji">
        Fiji
       </a>
       in 1872, with much of Oceania becoming part of the
       <a href="/wiki/British_Empire" title="British Empire">
        British Empire
       </a>
       . The
       <a href="/wiki/Gilbert_Islands" title="Gilbert Islands">
        Gilbert Islands
       </a>
       (now known as
       <a href="/wiki/Kiribati" title="Kiribati">
        Kiribati
       </a>
       ) and the Ellice Islands (now known as
       <a href="/wiki/Tuvalu" title="Tuvalu">
        Tuvalu
       </a>
       ) came under Britain's sphere of influence in the late 19th century.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-TAHNPT_53-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-TAHNPT-53">
         [53]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-54">
        <a href="#cite_note-54">
         [54]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       French Catholic missionaries arrived on Tahiti in 1834; their expulsion in 1836 caused France to send a gunboat in 1838. In 1842, Tahiti and
       <a href="/wiki/Tahuata" title="Tahuata">
        Tahuata
       </a>
       were declared a
       <a href="/wiki/Protectorate" title="Protectorate">
        French protectorate
       </a>
       , to allow Catholic missionaries to work undisturbed. The capital of
       <a href="/wiki/Papeete" title="Papeete">
        Papeetē
       </a>
       was founded in 1843.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-KMLA1889_55-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-KMLA1889-55">
         [55]
        </a>
       </sup>
       On 24 September 1853, under orders from
       <a href="/wiki/Napoleon_III" title="Napoleon III">
        Napoleon III
       </a>
       , Admiral
       <a href="/wiki/Auguste_Febvrier_Despointes" title="Auguste Febvrier Despointes">
        Febvrier Despointes
       </a>
       took formal possession of New Caledonia and
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Port-de-France" title="Port-de-France">
        Port-de-France
       </a>
       (Nouméa) was founded 25 June 1854.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ped_56-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-ped-56">
         [56]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       The Spanish explorer
       <a href="/wiki/Alonso_de_Salazar" title="Alonso de Salazar">
        Alonso de Salazar
       </a>
       landed in the Marshall Islands in 1529. They were named by
       <a href="/wiki/Adam_Johann_von_Krusenstern" title="Adam Johann von Krusenstern">
        Krusenstern
       </a>
       , after English
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Explorer" title="Explorer">
        explorer
       </a>
       <a href="/wiki/John_Marshall_(British_captain)" title="John Marshall (British captain)">
        John Marshall
       </a>
       , who visited them together with
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Thomas_Gilbert_(captain)" title="Thomas Gilbert (captain)">
        Thomas Gilbert
       </a>
       in 1788, en route from
       <a href="/wiki/Botany_Bay" title="Botany Bay">
        Botany Bay
       </a>
       to
       <a href="/wiki/Guangzhou" title="Guangzhou">
        Canton
       </a>
       (two ships of the
       <a href="/wiki/First_Fleet" title="First Fleet">
        First Fleet
       </a>
       ). In 1905 the British government transferred some administrative responsibility over south-east New Guinea to Australia (which renamed the area "
       <a href="/wiki/Territory_of_Papua" title="Territory of Papua">
        Territory of Papua
       </a>
       "); and in 1906, transferred all remaining responsibility to Australia. The Marshall Islands were claimed by Spain in 1874. Germany established colonies in
       <a href="/wiki/German_New_Guinea" title="German New Guinea">
        New Guinea
       </a>
       in 1884, and
       <a href="/wiki/German_Samoa" title="German Samoa">
        Samoa
       </a>
       in 1900. The United States also expanded into the Pacific, beginning with
       <a href="/wiki/Baker_Island" title="Baker Island">
        Baker Island
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Howland_Island" title="Howland Island">
        Howland Island
       </a>
       in 1857, and with Hawaii becoming a
       <a href="/wiki/Territory_of_Hawaii" title="Territory of Hawaii">
        U.S. territory
       </a>
       in 1898. Disagreements between the US, Germany and UK over Samoa led to the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Tripartite_Convention_(1899)" title="Tripartite Convention (1899)">
        Tripartite Convention of 1899
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-57">
        <a href="#cite_note-57">
         [57]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Modern_history">
        Modern history
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: Modern history">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       Main articles:
       <a href="/wiki/Pacific_War" title="Pacific War">
        Pacific War
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Military_history_of_Oceania" title="Military history of Oceania">
        Military history of Oceania
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Military_history_of_New_Zealand" title="Military history of New Zealand">
        Military history of New Zealand
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Military_history_of_Australia_during_World_War_I" title="Military history of Australia during World War I">
        Military history of Australia during World War I
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Military_history_of_Australia_during_World_War_II" title="Military history of Australia during World War II">
        Military history of Australia during World War II
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/History_of_Guam" title="History of Guam">
        History of Guam
       </a>
       , and
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/History_of_Australia_(1901%E2%80%931945)" title="History of Australia (1901–1945)">
        History of Australia (1901–1945)
       </a>
      </div>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:NZ_3rd_Division_(USMC_photo).jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="484" data-file-width="640" height="166" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/00/NZ_3rd_Division_%28USMC_photo%29.jpg/220px-NZ_3rd_Division_%28USMC_photo%29.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/00/NZ_3rd_Division_%28USMC_photo%29.jpg/330px-NZ_3rd_Division_%28USMC_photo%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/00/NZ_3rd_Division_%28USMC_photo%29.jpg/440px-NZ_3rd_Division_%28USMC_photo%29.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:NZ_3rd_Division_(USMC_photo).jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         New Zealand troops land on
         <a href="/wiki/Vella_Lavella" title="Vella Lavella">
          Vella Lavella
         </a>
         , in the
         <a href="/wiki/Solomon_Islands" title="Solomon Islands">
          Solomon Islands
         </a>
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       One of the first land offensives in Oceania was the
       <a href="/wiki/Occupation_of_German_Samoa" title="Occupation of German Samoa">
        Occupation of German Samoa
       </a>
       in August 1914 by
       <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_Defence_Force" title="New Zealand Defence Force">
        New Zealand forces
       </a>
       . The campaign to take Samoa ended without bloodshed after over 1,000 New Zealanders landed on the German
       <a href="/wiki/Colony" title="Colony">
        colony
       </a>
       . Australian forces attacked
       <a href="/wiki/German_New_Guinea" title="German New Guinea">
        German New Guinea
       </a>
       in September 1914. A company of Australians and a British warship besieged the Germans and their colonial subjects, ending with a German surrender.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-awm.gov.au_58-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-awm.gov.au-58">
         [58]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       The
       <a href="/wiki/Attack_on_Pearl_Harbor" title="Attack on Pearl Harbor">
        attack on Pearl Harbor
       </a>
       by the Japanese
       <a href="/wiki/Imperial_General_Headquarters" title="Imperial General Headquarters">
        Imperial General Headquarters
       </a>
       ,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-59">
        <a href="#cite_note-59">
         [59]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-60">
        <a href="#cite_note-60">
         [60]
        </a>
       </sup>
       was a surprise
       <a href="/wiki/Military_strike" title="Military strike">
        military strike
       </a>
       conducted by the
       <a href="/wiki/Imperial_Japanese_Navy" title="Imperial Japanese Navy">
        Imperial Japanese Navy
       </a>
       against the United States
       <a href="/wiki/Naval_base" title="Naval base">
        naval base
       </a>
       at
       <a href="/wiki/Pearl_Harbor" title="Pearl Harbor">
        Pearl Harbor
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Hawaii" title="Hawaii">
        Hawaii
       </a>
       , on the morning of 7 December 1941. The attack led to the
       <a href="/wiki/Military_history_of_the_United_States_during_World_War_II" title="Military history of the United States during World War II">
        United States' entry into World War II
       </a>
       . The Japanese subsequently invaded New Guinea, the Solomon Islands and other Pacific islands. The Japanese were turned back at the
       <a href="/wiki/Battle_of_the_Coral_Sea" title="Battle of the Coral Sea">
        Battle of the Coral Sea
       </a>
       and the
       <a href="/wiki/Kokoda_Track_campaign" title="Kokoda Track campaign">
        Kokoda Track campaign
       </a>
       before they were finally defeated in 1945. Some of the most prominent Oceanic battlegrounds were the
       <a href="/wiki/Battle_of_Bita_Paka" title="Battle of Bita Paka">
        Battle of Bita Paka
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Solomon_Islands_campaign" title="Solomon Islands campaign">
        Solomon Islands campaign
       </a>
       , the
       <a href="/wiki/Bombing_of_Darwin" title="Bombing of Darwin">
        Air raids on Darwin
       </a>
       , the
       <a href="/wiki/Kokoda_Track_campaign" title="Kokoda Track campaign">
        Kokada Track
       </a>
       , and the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Borneo_campaign" title="Borneo campaign">
        Borneo campaign
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-61">
        <a href="#cite_note-61">
         [61]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-62">
        <a href="#cite_note-62">
         [62]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The United States fought the
       <a href="/wiki/Battle_of_Guam_(1944)" title="Battle of Guam (1944)">
        Battle of Guam
       </a>
       from July 21 to August 10, 1944, to recapture the island from
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Japanese_military" title="Japanese military">
        Japanese military
       </a>
       occupation.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-63">
        <a href="#cite_note-63">
         [63]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       Australia and New Zealand became
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/British_Dominions" title="British Dominions">
        dominions
       </a>
       in the 20th century, adopting the
       <a href="/wiki/Statute_of_Westminster_1931" title="Statute of Westminster 1931">
        Statute of Westminster Act
       </a>
       in 1942 and 1947 respectively. In 1946, Polynesians were granted French citizenship and the islands' status was changed to an
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Overseas_administrative_territorial_entity" title="Overseas administrative territorial entity">
        overseas territory
       </a>
       ; the islands' name was changed in 1957 to
       <i>
        Polynésie Française
       </i>
       (
       <a href="/wiki/French_Polynesia" title="French Polynesia">
        French Polynesia
       </a>
       ). Hawaii became a
       <a href="/wiki/U.S._state" title="U.S. state">
        U.S. state
       </a>
       in 1959.
       <a href="/wiki/Fiji" title="Fiji">
        Fiji
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Tonga" title="Tonga">
        Tonga
       </a>
       became independent in 1970. On 1 May 1979, in recognition of the evolving political status of the
       <a href="/wiki/Marshall_Islands" title="Marshall Islands">
        Marshall Islands
       </a>
       , the
       <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">
        United States
       </a>
       recognized the constitution of the Marshall Islands and the establishment of the Government of the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Republic_of_the_Marshall_Islands" title="Republic of the Marshall Islands">
        Republic of the Marshall Islands
       </a>
       . The South Pacific Forum was founded in 1971, which became the
       <a href="/wiki/Pacific_Islands_Forum" title="Pacific Islands Forum">
        Pacific Islands Forum
       </a>
       in 2000.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-awm.gov.au_58-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-awm.gov.au-58">
         [58]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h2>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Geography">
        Geography
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Geography">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h2>
      <p>
       <span id="Territories_and_regions">
       </span>
      </p>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       See also:
       <a href="/wiki/List_of_Oceanian_countries_by_population" title="List of Oceanian countries by population">
        List of Oceanian countries by population
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/List_of_sovereign_states_and_dependent_territories_in_Oceania" title="List of sovereign states and dependent territories in Oceania">
        List of sovereign states and dependent territories in Oceania
       </a>
      </div>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:202px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Aoraki_Mount_Cook.JPG">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="2816" data-file-width="2112" height="267" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bf/Aoraki_Mount_Cook.JPG/200px-Aoraki_Mount_Cook.JPG" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bf/Aoraki_Mount_Cook.JPG/300px-Aoraki_Mount_Cook.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bf/Aoraki_Mount_Cook.JPG/400px-Aoraki_Mount_Cook.JPG 2x" width="200"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Aoraki_Mount_Cook.JPG" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         <a href="/wiki/Aoraki_/_Mount_Cook" title="Aoraki / Mount Cook">
          Aoraki / Mount Cook
         </a>
         , located on the
         <a href="/wiki/South_Island" title="South Island">
          South Island
         </a>
         of New Zealand
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:202px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Puncakjaya.jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="480" data-file-width="640" height="150" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3f/Puncakjaya.jpg/200px-Puncakjaya.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3f/Puncakjaya.jpg/300px-Puncakjaya.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3f/Puncakjaya.jpg/400px-Puncakjaya.jpg 2x" width="200"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Puncakjaya.jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         <a href="/wiki/Puncak_Jaya" title="Puncak Jaya">
          Puncak Jaya
         </a>
         /
         <i>
          Carstensz Pyramid
         </i>
         , highest
         <a href="/wiki/Summit" title="Summit">
          summit
         </a>
         in Oceania
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:202px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Oceania_satellite.jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="1155" data-file-width="2349" height="98" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Oceania_satellite.jpg/200px-Oceania_satellite.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Oceania_satellite.jpg/300px-Oceania_satellite.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Oceania_satellite.jpg/400px-Oceania_satellite.jpg 2x" width="200"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Oceania_satellite.jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         Satellite image of Oceania
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       Oceania was originally conceived as the lands of the Pacific Ocean, stretching from the
       <a href="/wiki/Strait_of_Malacca" title="Strait of Malacca">
        Strait of Malacca
       </a>
       to the coast of the Americas. It comprised four regions:
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Polynesia" title="Polynesia">
         Polynesia
        </a>
       </i>
       ,
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Micronesia" title="Micronesia">
         Micronesia
        </a>
       </i>
       ,
       <i>
        Malaysia
       </i>
       (now called the
       <a href="/wiki/Malay_Archipelago" title="Malay Archipelago">
        Malay Archipelago
       </a>
       ), and
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Melanesia" title="Melanesia">
         Melanesia
        </a>
       </i>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-64">
        <a href="#cite_note-64">
         [64]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Today, parts of three geological continents are included in the term "Oceania":
       <a href="/wiki/Eurasia" title="Eurasia">
        Eurasia
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Australia_(continent)" title="Australia (continent)">
        Australia
       </a>
       , and
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Zealandia_(continent)" title="Zealandia (continent)">
        Zealandia
       </a>
       , as well the non-continental volcanic islands of the
       <a href="/wiki/Philippines" title="Philippines">
        Philippines
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Wallacea" title="Wallacea">
        Wallacea
       </a>
       , and the open Pacific.
      </p>
      <p>
       Oceania extends to
       <a href="/wiki/New_Guinea" title="New Guinea">
        New Guinea
       </a>
       in the west, the
       <a href="/wiki/Bonin_Islands" title="Bonin Islands">
        Bonin Islands
       </a>
       in the northwest, the
       <a href="/wiki/Hawaiian_Islands" title="Hawaiian Islands">
        Hawaiian Islands
       </a>
       in the northeast,
       <a href="/wiki/Easter_Island" title="Easter Island">
        Rapa Nui
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Isla_Salas_y_G%C3%B3mez" title="Isla Salas y Gómez">
        Sala y Gómez Island
       </a>
       in the east, and
       <a href="/wiki/Macquarie_Island" title="Macquarie Island">
        Macquarie Island
       </a>
       in the south. Not included are the Pacific islands of
       <a href="/wiki/Taiwan" title="Taiwan">
        Taiwan
       </a>
       , the
       <a href="/wiki/Ryukyu_Islands" title="Ryukyu Islands">
        Ryukyu Islands
       </a>
       , the
       <a href="/wiki/Japanese_archipelago" title="Japanese archipelago">
        Japanese archipelago
       </a>
       , and the
       <a href="/wiki/Maluku_Islands" title="Maluku Islands">
        Maluku Islands
       </a>
       , all on the margins of Asia, and the
       <a href="/wiki/Aleutian_Islands" title="Aleutian Islands">
        Aleutian Islands
       </a>
       of North America. In its periphery, Oceania sprawls
       <a href="/wiki/28th_parallel_north" title="28th parallel north">
        28 degrees north
       </a>
       to the Bonin Islands in the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Northern_hemisphere" title="Northern hemisphere">
        northern hemisphere
       </a>
       , and
       <a href="/wiki/55th_parallel_south" title="55th parallel south">
        55 degrees south
       </a>
       to Macquarie Island in the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Southern_hemisphere" title="Southern hemisphere">
        southern hemisphere
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-65">
        <a href="#cite_note-65">
         [65]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       Oceanian islands are of four basic types: continental islands,
       <a href="/wiki/High_island" title="High island">
        high islands
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Coral_reef" title="Coral reef">
        coral reefs
       </a>
       and uplifted
       <a href="/wiki/Coral_island" title="Coral island">
        coral platforms
       </a>
       . High islands are of volcanic origin, and many contain active volcanoes. Among these are
       <a href="/wiki/Bougainville_Island" title="Bougainville Island">
        Bougainville
       </a>
       , Hawaii, and the Solomon Islands.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-GillespieClague2009_66-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-GillespieClague2009-66">
         [66]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       Oceania is one of eight terrestrial
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Ecozone" title="Ecozone">
        ecozones
       </a>
       , which constitute the major ecological regions of the planet. Related to these concepts are
       <a href="/wiki/Near_Oceania" title="Near Oceania">
        Near Oceania
       </a>
       , that part of western
       <a href="/wiki/Island_Melanesia" title="Island Melanesia">
        Island Melanesia
       </a>
       which has been inhabited for tens of millennia, and
       <a href="/wiki/Remote_Oceania" title="Remote Oceania">
        Remote Oceania
       </a>
       which is more recently settled. Although the majority of the Oceanian islands lie in the South Pacific, a few of them are not restricted to the
       <a href="/wiki/Pacific_Ocean" title="Pacific Ocean">
        Pacific Ocean
       </a>
       —
       <a href="/wiki/Kangaroo_Island" title="Kangaroo Island">
        Kangaroo Island
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Ashmore_and_Cartier_Islands" title="Ashmore and Cartier Islands">
        Ashmore and Cartier Islands
       </a>
       , for instance, are situated in the
       <a href="/wiki/Southern_Ocean" title="Southern Ocean">
        Southern Ocean
       </a>
       and
