       <a href="/wiki/Indian_Ocean" title="Indian Ocean">
        Indian Ocean
       </a>
       , respectively, and
       <a href="/wiki/West_Coast,_Tasmania" title="West Coast, Tasmania">
        Tasmania's west coast
       </a>
       faces the Southern Ocean.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-67">
        <a href="#cite_note-67">
         [67]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       The
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Coral_reefs" title="Coral reefs">
        coral reefs
       </a>
       of the South Pacific are low-lying structures that have built up on basaltic lava flows under the ocean's surface. One of the most dramatic is the
       <a href="/wiki/Great_Barrier_Reef" title="Great Barrier Reef">
        Great Barrier Reef
       </a>
       off northeastern
       <a href="/wiki/Australia" title="Australia">
        Australia
       </a>
       with chains of reef patches. A second island type formed of coral is the uplifted coral platform, which is usually slightly larger than the low coral islands. Examples include
       <a href="/wiki/Banaba_Island" title="Banaba Island">
        Banaba
       </a>
       (formerly Ocean Island) and
       <a href="/wiki/Makatea" title="Makatea">
        Makatea
       </a>
       in the Tuamotu group of
       <a href="/wiki/French_Polynesia" title="French Polynesia">
        French Polynesia
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-68">
        <a href="#cite_note-68">
         [68]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-69">
        <a href="#cite_note-69">
         [69]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Regions">
        Regions
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Regions">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <p>
       <a href="/wiki/Micronesia" title="Micronesia">
        Micronesia
       </a>
       , which lies north of the equator and west of the
       <a href="/wiki/International_Date_Line" title="International Date Line">
        International Date Line
       </a>
       , includes the
       <a href="/wiki/Mariana_Islands" title="Mariana Islands">
        Mariana Islands
       </a>
       in the northwest, the
       <a href="/wiki/Caroline_Islands" title="Caroline Islands">
        Caroline Islands
       </a>
       in the center, the
       <a href="/wiki/Marshall_Islands" title="Marshall Islands">
        Marshall Islands
       </a>
       to the west and the islands of
       <a href="/wiki/Kiribati" title="Kiribati">
        Kiribati
       </a>
       in the southeast.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-AAE_70-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-AAE-70">
         [70]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-LalFortune2000p63_71-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-LalFortune2000p63-71">
         [71]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       <a href="/wiki/Melanesia" title="Melanesia">
        Melanesia
       </a>
       , to the southwest, includes
       <a href="/wiki/New_Guinea" title="New Guinea">
        New Guinea
       </a>
       , the world's second largest island after
       <a href="/wiki/Greenland" title="Greenland">
        Greenland
       </a>
       and by far the largest of the Pacific islands. The other main Melanesian groups from north to south are the
       <a href="/wiki/Bismarck_Archipelago" title="Bismarck Archipelago">
        Bismarck Archipelago
       </a>
       , the
       <a href="/wiki/Solomon_Islands" title="Solomon Islands">
        Solomon Islands
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Santa_Cruz_Islands" title="Santa Cruz Islands">
        Santa Cruz
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Vanuatu" title="Vanuatu">
        Vanuatu
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Fiji" title="Fiji">
        Fiji
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/New_Caledonia" title="New Caledonia">
        New Caledonia
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-West2009_72-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-West2009-72">
         [72]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       <a href="/wiki/Polynesia" title="Polynesia">
        Polynesia
       </a>
       , stretching from
       <a href="/wiki/Hawaii" title="Hawaii">
        Hawaii
       </a>
       in the north to
       <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand" title="New Zealand">
        New Zealand
       </a>
       in the south, also encompasses
       <a href="/wiki/Tuvalu" title="Tuvalu">
        Tuvalu
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Tokelau" title="Tokelau">
        Tokelau
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Samoa" title="Samoa">
        Samoa
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Tonga" title="Tonga">
        Tonga
       </a>
       and the
       <a href="/wiki/Kermadec_Islands" title="Kermadec Islands">
        Kermadec Islands
       </a>
       to the west, the
       <a href="/wiki/Cook_Islands" title="Cook Islands">
        Cook Islands
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Society_Islands" title="Society Islands">
        Society Islands
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Austral_Islands" title="Austral Islands">
        Austral Islands
       </a>
       in the center, and the
       <a href="/wiki/Marquesas_Islands" title="Marquesas Islands">
        Marquesas Islands
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Tuamotus" title="Tuamotus">
        Tuamotu
       </a>
       ,
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Mangareva_Islands" title="Mangareva Islands">
        Mangareva Islands
       </a>
       , and
       <a href="/wiki/Easter_Island" title="Easter Island">
        Easter Island
       </a>
       to the east.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-DunfordRidgell1996_73-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-DunfordRidgell1996-73">
         [73]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       <a href="/wiki/Australasia" title="Australasia">
        Australasia
       </a>
       comprises
       <a href="/wiki/Australia" title="Australia">
        Australia
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand" title="New Zealand">
        New Zealand
       </a>
       , the island of
       <a href="/wiki/New_Guinea" title="New Guinea">
        New Guinea
       </a>
       , and neighbouring
       <a href="/wiki/Island" title="Island">
        islands
       </a>
       in the
       <a href="/wiki/Pacific_Ocean" title="Pacific Ocean">
        Pacific Ocean
       </a>
       . Most of Australasia lies on the southern portion of the
       <a href="/wiki/Indo-Australian_Plate" title="Indo-Australian Plate">
        Indo-Australian Plate
       </a>
       , flanked by the
       <a href="/wiki/Indian_Ocean" title="Indian Ocean">
        Indian Ocean
       </a>
       to the west and the
       <a href="/wiki/Southern_Ocean" title="Southern Ocean">
        Southern Ocean
       </a>
       to the south.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-74">
        <a href="#cite_note-74">
         [74]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The bulk of Australasia sits on the
       <a href="/wiki/Indo-Australian_Plate" title="Indo-Australian Plate">
        Indo-Australian Plate
       </a>
       , together with
       <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">
        India
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-75">
        <a href="#cite_note-75">
         [75]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Geology">
        Geology
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: Geology">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       Main articles:
       <a href="/wiki/Geography_of_Fiji" title="Geography of Fiji">
        Geography of Fiji
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Geology_of_New_Zealand" title="Geology of New Zealand">
        Geology of New Zealand
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Geology_of_Australia" title="Geology of Australia">
        Geology of Australia
       </a>
       , and
       <a href="/wiki/Geography_of_Samoa" title="Geography of Samoa">
        Geography of Samoa
       </a>
      </div>
      <div class="thumb tleft">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Plaque_Pacifique.JPG">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="1134" data-file-width="1134" height="220" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/af/Plaque_Pacifique.JPG/220px-Plaque_Pacifique.JPG" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/af/Plaque_Pacifique.JPG/330px-Plaque_Pacifique.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/af/Plaque_Pacifique.JPG/440px-Plaque_Pacifique.JPG 2x" width="220"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Plaque_Pacifique.JPG" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         The
         <a href="/wiki/Pacific_Plate" title="Pacific Plate">
          Pacific Plate
         </a>
         comprises most of Oceanian regions, excluding
         <a href="/wiki/Australasia" title="Australasia">
          Australasia
         </a>
         and western portion of
         <a href="/wiki/Melanesia" title="Melanesia">
          Melanesia
         </a>
         .
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       The
       <a href="/wiki/Pacific_Plate" title="Pacific Plate">
        Pacific Plate
       </a>
       , which makes up most of Oceania, is an oceanic
       <a href="/wiki/Plate_tectonics" title="Plate tectonics">
        tectonic plate
       </a>
       that lies beneath the
       <a href="/wiki/Pacific_Ocean" title="Pacific Ocean">
        Pacific Ocean
       </a>
       . At 103 million square kilometres (40,000,000 sq mi), it is the largest tectonic plate. The plate contains an interior
       <a href="/wiki/Hotspot_(geology)" title="Hotspot (geology)">
        hot spot
       </a>
       forming the
       <a href="/wiki/Hawaiian_Islands" title="Hawaiian Islands">
        Hawaiian Islands
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-76">
        <a href="#cite_note-76">
         [76]
        </a>
       </sup>
       It is almost entirely
       <a href="/wiki/Oceanic_crust" title="Oceanic crust">
        oceanic crust
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-77">
        <a href="#cite_note-77">
         [77]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The oldest member disappearing by way of the
       <a href="/wiki/Plate_tectonics" title="Plate tectonics">
        plate tectonics
       </a>
       cycle is early-
       <a href="/wiki/Cretaceous" title="Cretaceous">
        Cretaceous
       </a>
       (145 to 137 million years ago).
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-78">
        <a href="#cite_note-78">
         [78]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       Australia, being part of the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Indo-Australian_plate" title="Indo-Australian plate">
        Indo-Australian plate
       </a>
       , is the lowest, flattest, and oldest landmass on Earth
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-79">
        <a href="#cite_note-79">
         [79]
        </a>
       </sup>
       and it has had a relatively stable geological history. Geological forces such as
       <a href="/wiki/Tectonic_uplift" title="Tectonic uplift">
        tectonic uplift
       </a>
       of mountain ranges or clashes between tectonic plates occurred mainly in Australia's early history, when it was still a part of
       <a href="/wiki/Gondwana" title="Gondwana">
        Gondwana
       </a>
       . Australia is situated in the middle of the tectonic plate, and therefore currently has no active volcanism.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ag_80-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-ag-80">
         [80]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       The
       <a href="/wiki/Geology" title="Geology">
        geology
       </a>
       of
       <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand" title="New Zealand">
        New Zealand
       </a>
       is noted for its
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Volcanic" title="Volcanic">
        volcanic
       </a>
       activity,
       <a href="/wiki/Earthquake" title="Earthquake">
        earthquakes
       </a>
       and
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Geothermal" title="Geothermal">
        geothermal
       </a>
       <a href="/wiki/Geothermal_areas_in_New_Zealand" title="Geothermal areas in New Zealand">
        areas
       </a>
       because of its position on the boundary of the
       <a href="/wiki/Australian_Plate" title="Australian Plate">
        Australian Plate
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Pacific_Plate" title="Pacific Plate">
        Pacific Plates
       </a>
       . Much of the basement rock of New Zealand was once part of the super-continent of
       <a href="/wiki/Gondwana" title="Gondwana">
        Gondwana
       </a>
       , along with
       <a href="/wiki/South_America" title="South America">
        South America
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Africa" title="Africa">
        Africa
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Madagascar" title="Madagascar">
        Madagascar
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">
        India
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Antarctica" title="Antarctica">
        Antarctica
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Australia" title="Australia">
        Australia
       </a>
       . The rocks that now form the continent of
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Zealandia_(continent)" title="Zealandia (continent)">
        Zealandia
       </a>
       were nestled between Eastern Australia and
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Western_Antarctica" title="Western Antarctica">
        Western Antarctica
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-81">
        <a href="#cite_note-81">
         [81]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       The Australia-New Zealand continental fragment of
       <a href="/wiki/Gondwana" title="Gondwana">
        Gondwana
       </a>
       split from the rest of Gondwana in the
       <a href="/wiki/Late_Cretaceous" title="Late Cretaceous">
        late Cretaceous
       </a>
       time (95–90 Ma). By 75 Ma,
       <a href="/wiki/Zealandia" title="Zealandia">
        Zealandia
       </a>
       was essentially separate from Australia and
       <a href="/wiki/Antarctica" title="Antarctica">
        Antarctica
       </a>
       , although only shallow seas might have separated Zealandia and Australia in the north. The
       <a href="/wiki/Tasman_Sea" title="Tasman Sea">
        Tasman Sea
       </a>
       , and part of Zealandia then locked together with Australia to form the
       <a href="/wiki/Australian_Plate" title="Australian Plate">
        Australian Plate
       </a>
       (40 Ma), and a new plate boundary was created between the Australian Plate and
       <a href="/wiki/Pacific_Plate" title="Pacific Plate">
        Pacific Plate
       </a>
       .
      </p>
      <p>
       Most islands in the Pacific are
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/High_islands" title="High islands">
        high islands
       </a>
       (
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Volcanic" title="Volcanic">
        volcanic
       </a>
       islands), such as,
       <a href="/wiki/Easter_Island" title="Easter Island">
        Easter Island
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/American_Samoa" title="American Samoa">
        American Samoa
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Fiji" title="Fiji">
        Fiji
       </a>
       , among others, having peaks up to 1300 m rising abruptly from the shore.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Factbook-Fiji_82-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-Factbook-Fiji-82">
         [82]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The
       <a href="/wiki/Northwestern_Hawaiian_Islands" title="Northwestern Hawaiian Islands">
        Northwestern Hawaiian Islands
       </a>
       were formed approximately 7 to 30 million years ago, as
       <a href="/wiki/Shield_volcano" title="Shield volcano">
        shield volcanoes
       </a>
       over the same volcanic
       <a href="/wiki/Hotspot_(geology)" title="Hotspot (geology)">
        hotspot
       </a>
       that formed the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Emperor_Seamounts" title="Emperor Seamounts">
        Emperor Seamounts
       </a>
       to the north and the Main Hawaiian Islands to the south.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-83">
        <a href="#cite_note-83">
         [83]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Hawaii's tallest mountain
       <a href="/wiki/Mauna_Kea" title="Mauna Kea">
        Mauna Kea
       </a>
       is 13,796 ft (4,205 m) above mean sea level.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-84">
        <a href="#cite_note-84">
         [84]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Flora">
        Flora
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Flora">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       Main articles:
       <a href="/wiki/Geography_of_Australia" title="Geography of Australia">
        Geography of Australia
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Environment_of_New_Zealand" title="Environment of New Zealand">
        Environment of New Zealand
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Flora_of_Australia" title="Flora of Australia">
        Flora of Australia
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Flora_of_New_Zealand" title="Flora of New Zealand">
        Flora of New Zealand
       </a>
       , and
       <a href="/wiki/Endemism_in_the_Hawaiian_Islands" title="Endemism in the Hawaiian Islands">
        Endemism in the Hawaiian Islands
       </a>
      </div>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Countryside_Kaikoura,_New_Zealand.JPG">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="480" data-file-width="640" height="165" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/da/Countryside_Kaikoura%2C_New_Zealand.JPG/220px-Countryside_Kaikoura%2C_New_Zealand.JPG" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/da/Countryside_Kaikoura%2C_New_Zealand.JPG/330px-Countryside_Kaikoura%2C_New_Zealand.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/da/Countryside_Kaikoura%2C_New_Zealand.JPG/440px-Countryside_Kaikoura%2C_New_Zealand.JPG 2x" width="220"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Countryside_Kaikoura,_New_Zealand.JPG" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         New Zealand countryside
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Ulu%E1%B9%9Fu_(Ayers_Rock),_Sunset.jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="2233" data-file-width="3573" height="137" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2f/Ulu%E1%B9%9Fu_%28Ayers_Rock%29%2C_Sunset.jpg/220px-Ulu%E1%B9%9Fu_%28Ayers_Rock%29%2C_Sunset.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2f/Ulu%E1%B9%9Fu_%28Ayers_Rock%29%2C_Sunset.jpg/330px-Ulu%E1%B9%9Fu_%28Ayers_Rock%29%2C_Sunset.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2f/Ulu%E1%B9%9Fu_%28Ayers_Rock%29%2C_Sunset.jpg/440px-Ulu%E1%B9%9Fu_%28Ayers_Rock%29%2C_Sunset.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Ulu%E1%B9%9Fu_(Ayers_Rock),_Sunset.jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         <a href="/wiki/Uluru" title="Uluru">
          Uluru
         </a>
         in
         <a href="/wiki/Central_Australia" title="Central Australia">
          Central Australia
         </a>
         .
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       The most diverse country of Oceania when it comes to the environment is Australia, with tropical
       <a href="/wiki/Rainforest" title="Rainforest">
        rainforests
       </a>
       in the north-east, mountain ranges in the south-east, south-west and east, and dry desert in the centre.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-85">
        <a href="#cite_note-85">
         [85]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Deserts_of_Australia" title="Deserts of Australia">
        Desert
       </a>
       or semi-arid land commonly known as the
       <a href="/wiki/Outback" title="Outback">
        outback
       </a>
       makes up by far the largest portion of land.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-portrait_86-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-portrait-86">
         [86]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The
       <a href="/wiki/Eastern_Australian_temperate_forests" title="Eastern Australian temperate forests">
        coastal uplands
       </a>
       and a
       <a href="/wiki/Brigalow_Belt" title="Brigalow Belt">
        belt of Brigalow grasslands
       </a>
       lie between the coast and the mountains, while inland of the dividing range are large areas of grassland.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-87">
        <a href="#cite_note-87">
         [87]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The northernmost point of the east coast is the tropical-rainforested
       <a href="/wiki/Cape_York_Peninsula" title="Cape York Peninsula">
        Cape York Peninsula
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-88">
        <a href="#cite_note-88">
         [88]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-89">
        <a href="#cite_note-89">
         [89]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-90">
        <a href="#cite_note-90">
         [90]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-91">
        <a href="#cite_note-91">
         [91]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-92">
        <a href="#cite_note-92">
         [92]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       Prominent features of the Australian flora are adaptations to
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Aridity" title="Aridity">
        aridity
       </a>
       and fire which include
       <a href="/wiki/Sclerophyll" title="Sclerophyll">
        scleromorphy
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Serotiny" title="Serotiny">
        serotiny
       </a>
       . These adaptations are common in species from the large and well-known families
       <a href="/wiki/Proteaceae" title="Proteaceae">
        Proteaceae
       </a>
       (
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Banksia" title="Banksia">
         Banksia
        </a>
       </i>
       ),
       <a href="/wiki/Myrtaceae" title="Myrtaceae">
        Myrtaceae
       </a>
       (
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Eucalyptus" title="Eucalyptus">
         Eucalyptus
        </a>
       </i>
       – gum trees), and
       <a href="/wiki/Fabaceae" title="Fabaceae">
        Fabaceae
       </a>
       (
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Acacia" title="Acacia">
         Acacia
        </a>
       </i>
       – wattle). The flora of Fiji,
       <a href="/wiki/Solomon_Islands" title="Solomon Islands">
        Solomon Islands
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Vanuatu" title="Vanuatu">
        Vanuatu
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/New_Caledonia" title="New Caledonia">
        New Caledonia
       </a>
       is
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Tropical_dry_forest" title="Tropical dry forest">
        tropical dry forest
       </a>
       , with
       <a href="/wiki/Tropical_vegetation" title="Tropical vegetation">
        tropical vegetation
       </a>
       that includes
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Palm_trees" title="Palm trees">
        palm trees
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Premna_protrusa" title="Premna protrusa">
        premna protrusa
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Psydrax_odorata" title="Psydrax odorata">
        psydrax odorata
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Gyrocarpus_americanus" title="Gyrocarpus americanus">
        gyrocarpus americanus
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Derris_trifoliata" title="Derris trifoliata">
        derris trifoliata
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-93">
        <a href="#cite_note-93">
         [93]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       New Zealand's landscape ranges from the
       <a href="/wiki/Fjord" title="Fjord">
        fjord
       </a>
       -like sounds of the southwest to the tropical beaches of the far north. South Island is dominated by the
       <a href="/wiki/Southern_Alps" title="Southern Alps">
        Southern Alps
       </a>
       . There are 18 peaks of more than 3000 metres (9800 ft) in the South Island. All summits over 2,900 m are within the Southern Alps, a chain that forms the backbone of the South Island; the highest peak of which is
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Aoraki/Mount_Cook" title="Aoraki/Mount Cook">
        Aoraki/Mount Cook
       </a>
       , at 3,754 metres (12,316 ft).
       <a href="/wiki/Earthquake" title="Earthquake">
        Earthquakes
       </a>
       are common, though usually not severe, averaging 3,000 per year.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-94">
        <a href="#cite_note-94">
         [94]
        </a>
       </sup>
       There is a wide variety of native
       <a href="/wiki/Tree" title="Tree">
        trees
       </a>
       , adapted to all the various micro-
       <a href="/wiki/Climate" title="Climate">
        climates
       </a>
       in New Zealand.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-95">
        <a href="#cite_note-95">
         [95]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       In Hawaii, one endemic plant,
       <i>
        <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Brighamia" title="Brighamia">
         Brighamia
        </a>
       </i>
       , now requires hand-pollination because its natural pollinator is presumed to be extinct.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-96">
        <a href="#cite_note-96">
         [96]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The two species of
       <i>
        Brighamia
       </i>
       —
       <i>
        B. rockii
       </i>
       and
       <i>
        B. insignis
       </i>
       —are represented in the wild by around 120 individual plants. To ensure these plants set seed, biologists rappel down 3,000-foot (910 m) cliffs to brush pollen onto their stigmas.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-97">
        <a href="#cite_note-97">
         [97]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Fauna">
        Fauna
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Fauna">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       Main articles:
       <a href="/wiki/Fauna_of_Australia" title="Fauna of Australia">
        Fauna of Australia
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Birds_of_Australia" title="Birds of Australia">
        Birds of Australia
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Birds_of_New_Zealand" title="Birds of New Zealand">
        Birds of New Zealand
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Fauna_of_New_Zealand" title="Fauna of New Zealand">
        Fauna of New Zealand
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Mammals_of_Australia" title="Mammals of Australia">
        Mammals of Australia
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/List_of_birds_of_Australia" title="List of birds of Australia">
        List of birds of Australia
       </a>
       , and
       <a href="/wiki/List_of_birds_of_New_Zealand" title="List of birds of New Zealand">
        List of birds of New Zealand
       </a>
      </div>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:162px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Pacific_Robin_(25643350344).jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="2260" data-file-width="1577" height="229" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/Pacific_Robin_%2825643350344%29.jpg/160px-Pacific_Robin_%2825643350344%29.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/Pacific_Robin_%2825643350344%29.jpg/240px-Pacific_Robin_%2825643350344%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/Pacific_Robin_%2825643350344%29.jpg/320px-Pacific_Robin_%2825643350344%29.jpg 2x" width="160"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Pacific_Robin_(25643350344).jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         The
         <a href="/wiki/Pacific_robin" title="Pacific robin">
          Pacific robin
         </a>
         inhabits the islands of the south western Pacific.
         <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-IUCN_98-0">
          <a href="#cite_note-IUCN-98">
           [98]
          </a>
         </sup>
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       The aptly-named
       <a href="/wiki/Pacific_kingfisher" title="Pacific kingfisher">
        Pacific kingfisher
       </a>
       is found in the Pacific Islands,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-99">
        <a href="#cite_note-99">
         [99]
        </a>
       </sup>
       as is the
       <a href="/wiki/Red-vented_bulbul" title="Red-vented bulbul">
        Red-vented bulbul
       </a>
       ,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-100">
        <a href="#cite_note-100">
         [100]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Polynesian_starling" title="Polynesian starling">
        Polynesian starling
       </a>
       ,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-101">
        <a href="#cite_note-101">
         [101]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Brown_goshawk" title="Brown goshawk">
        Brown goshawk
       </a>
       ,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-102">
        <a href="#cite_note-102">
         [102]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Pacific_Swallow" title="Pacific Swallow">
        Pacific Swallow
       </a>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Turner_103-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-Turner-103">
         [103]
        </a>
       </sup>
       and the
       <a href="/wiki/Cardinal_myzomela" title="Cardinal myzomela">
        Cardinal myzomela
       </a>
       , among others.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-104">
        <a href="#cite_note-104">
         [104]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Birds breeding on
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Pitcairn" title="Pitcairn">
        Pitcairn
       </a>
       include the
       <a href="/wiki/Fairy_tern" title="Fairy tern">
        fairy tern
       </a>
       ,
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Common_noddy" title="Common noddy">
        common noddy
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Red-tailed_tropicbird" title="Red-tailed tropicbird">
        red-tailed tropicbird
       </a>
       . The
       <a href="/wiki/Pitcairn_reed_warbler" title="Pitcairn reed warbler">
        Pitcairn reed warbler
       </a>
       , endemic to Pitcairn Island, was added to the
       <a href="/wiki/Endangered_species" title="Endangered species">
        endangered species
       </a>
       list in 2008.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-105">
        <a href="#cite_note-105">
         [105]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       Native to Hawaii is the
       <a href="/wiki/Hawaiian_crow" title="Hawaiian crow">
        Hawaiian crow
       </a>
       , which has been
       <a href="/wiki/Extinct_in_the_wild" title="Extinct in the wild">
        extinct in the wild
       </a>
       since 2002.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-106">
        <a href="#cite_note-106">
         [106]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The
       <a href="/wiki/Brown_tree_snake" title="Brown tree snake">
        brown tree snake
       </a>
       is native to northern and eastern coasts of Australia, Papua New Guinea, Guam and the Solomon Islands.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-107">
        <a href="#cite_note-107">
         [107]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Native to Australia, New Guinea and proximate islands are
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Birds_of_paradise" title="Birds of paradise">
        birds of paradise
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Honeyeater" title="Honeyeater">
        honeyeaters
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Australasian_treecreeper" title="Australasian treecreeper">
        Australasian treecreeper
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Australasian_robin" title="Australasian robin">
        Australasian robin
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Kingfisher" title="Kingfisher">
        kingfishers
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Butcherbird" title="Butcherbird">
        butcherbirds
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Bowerbird" title="Bowerbird">
        bowerbirds
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-108">
        <a href="#cite_note-108">
         [108]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Steadman_2006_109-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-Steadman_2006-109">
         [109]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       A unique feature of Australia's fauna is the relative scarcity of native
       <a href="/wiki/Placentalia" title="Placentalia">
        placental
       </a>
       mammals, and dominance of the
       <a href="/wiki/Marsupial" title="Marsupial">
        marsupials
       </a>
       — a group of mammals that raise their young in a
       <a href="/wiki/Pouch_(marsupial)" title="Pouch (marsupial)">
        pouch
       </a>
       , including the
       <a href="/wiki/Macropodidae" title="Macropodidae">
        macropods
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Phalangeriformes" title="Phalangeriformes">
        possums
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Dasyuromorphia" title="Dasyuromorphia">
        dasyuromorphs
       </a>
       . The
       <a href="/wiki/Passerine" title="Passerine">
        passerines
       </a>
       of Australia, also known as songbirds or perching birds, include
       <a href="/wiki/Wren" title="Wren">
        wrens
       </a>
       , the
       <a href="/wiki/Artamidae" title="Artamidae">
        magpie group
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Acanthiza" title="Acanthiza">
        thornbills
       </a>
       ,
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Corvid" title="Corvid">
        corvids
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Pardalote" title="Pardalote">
        pardalotes
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Lyrebird" title="Lyrebird">
        lyrebirds
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ioc_110-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-ioc-110">
         [110]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Predominant bird species in the country include the
       <a href="/wiki/Australian_magpie" title="Australian magpie">
        Australian magpie
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Australian_raven" title="Australian raven">
        Australian raven
       </a>
       , the
       <a href="/wiki/Pied_currawong" title="Pied currawong">
        pied currawong
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Crested_pigeon" title="Crested pigeon">
        crested pigeons
       </a>
       and the
       <a href="/wiki/Laughing_kookaburra" title="Laughing kookaburra">
        laughing kookaburra
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-111">
        <a href="#cite_note-111">
         [111]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The
       <a href="/wiki/Koala" title="Koala">
        koala
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Emu" title="Emu">
        emu
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Platypus" title="Platypus">
        platypus
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Kangaroo" title="Kangaroo">
        kangaroo
       </a>
       are
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/National_animals" title="National animals">
        national animals
       </a>
       of Australia,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-CoatArms_112-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-CoatArms-112">
         [112]
        </a>
       </sup>
       and the
       <a href="/wiki/Tasmanian_devil" title="Tasmanian devil">
        Tasmanian devil
       </a>
       is also one of the well-known animals in the country.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-113">
        <a href="#cite_note-113">
         [113]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The
       <a href="/wiki/Goanna" title="Goanna">
        goanna
       </a>
       is a
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Predatory" title="Predatory">
        predatory
       </a>
       lizard native to the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Australian_mainland" title="Australian mainland">
        Australian mainland
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-114">
        <a href="#cite_note-114">
         [114]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       The
       <a href="/wiki/Bird" title="Bird">
        birds
       </a>
       of
       <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand" title="New Zealand">
        New Zealand
       </a>
       evolved into an avifauna that included a large number of
       <a href="/wiki/Endemism" title="Endemism">
        endemic
       </a>
       species. As an island archipelago New Zealand accumulated bird diversity and when Captain James Cook arrived in the 1770s he noted that the
       <a href="/wiki/Bird_vocalization" title="Bird vocalization">
        bird song
       </a>
       was deafening. The mix includes species with unusual biology such as the
       <a href="/wiki/Kakapo" title="Kakapo">
        kakapo
       </a>
       which is the world's only flightless, nocturnal,
       <a href="/wiki/Lek_mating" title="Lek mating">
        lek breeding
       </a>
       parrot, but also many species that are similar to neighboring land areas. Some of the more well known and distinctive bird species in New Zealand are the
       <a href="/wiki/Kiwi" title="Kiwi">
        kiwi
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Kea" title="Kea">
        kea
       </a>
       ,
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Takahe" title="Takahe">
        takahe
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Kakapo" title="Kakapo">
        kakapo
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Yellowhead_(bird)" title="Yellowhead (bird)">
        mohua
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Tui_(bird)" title="Tui (bird)">
        tui
       </a>
       and the
       <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_bellbird" title="New Zealand bellbird">
        bellbird
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-115">
        <a href="#cite_note-115">
         [115]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The
       <a href="/wiki/Tuatara" title="Tuatara">
        tuatara
       </a>
       is a notable
       <a href="/wiki/Reptile" title="Reptile">
        reptile
       </a>
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Endemic" title="Endemic">
        endemic
       </a>
       to New Zealand.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-116">
        <a href="#cite_note-116">
         [116]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Climate">
        Climate
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: Climate">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       Main articles:
       <a href="/wiki/Climate_of_Australia" title="Climate of Australia">
        Climate of Australia
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Climate_of_New_Zealand" title="Climate of New Zealand">
        Climate of New Zealand
       </a>
       , and
       <a href="/wiki/Climate_of_Hawaii" title="Climate of Hawaii">
        Climate of Hawaii
       </a>
      </div>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:First_Church,_Dunedin,_NZ.jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="3253" data-file-width="3637" height="197" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/97/First_Church%2C_Dunedin%2C_NZ.jpg/220px-First_Church%2C_Dunedin%2C_NZ.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/97/First_Church%2C_Dunedin%2C_NZ.jpg/330px-First_Church%2C_Dunedin%2C_NZ.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/97/First_Church%2C_Dunedin%2C_NZ.jpg/440px-First_Church%2C_Dunedin%2C_NZ.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:First_Church,_Dunedin,_NZ.jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         August 2011 winter's snowfall in
         <a href="/wiki/Dunedin" title="Dunedin">
          Dunedin
         </a>
         ,
         <a href="/wiki/Otago" title="Otago">
          Otago
         </a>
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       The Pacific Islands are ruled by a
       <a href="/wiki/Tropical_rainforest" title="Tropical rainforest">
        tropical rainforest
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Tropical_savanna_climate" title="Tropical savanna climate">
        tropical savanna climate
       </a>
       . In the tropical and subtropical Pacific, the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/El_Ni%C3%B1o_Southern_Oscillation" title="El Niño Southern Oscillation">
        El Niño Southern Oscillation
       </a>
       (ENSO) affects weather conditions.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-117">
        <a href="#cite_note-117">
         [117]
        </a>
       </sup>
       In the tropical western Pacific, the
       <a href="/wiki/Monsoon" title="Monsoon">
        monsoon
       </a>
       and the related
       <a href="/wiki/Wet_season" title="Wet season">
        wet season
       </a>
       during the summer months contrast with dry winds in the winter which blow over the ocean from the Asian landmass.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-118">
        <a href="#cite_note-118">
         [118]
        </a>
       </sup>
       November is the only month in which all the
       <a href="/wiki/Tropical_cyclone_basins" title="Tropical cyclone basins">
        tropical cyclone basins
       </a>
       are active.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-AOML_FAQ_G1_119-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-AOML_FAQ_G1-119">
         [119]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       To the southwest of the region, in the Australian landmass, the climate is mostly
       <a href="/wiki/Desert" title="Desert">
        desert
       </a>
       or
       <a href="/wiki/Semi-arid_climate" title="Semi-arid climate">
        semi-arid
       </a>
       , with the southern coastal corners having a
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Temperateness" title="Temperateness">
        temperate
       </a>
       climate, such as
       <a href="/wiki/Oceanic_climate" title="Oceanic climate">
        oceanic
       </a>
       and
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Humid_subtropical" title="Humid subtropical">
        humid subtropical
       </a>
       climate in the east coast and
       <a href="/wiki/Mediterranean_climate" title="Mediterranean climate">
        Mediterranean climate
       </a>
       in the west. The northern parts of the country have a
       <a href="/wiki/Tropical_climate" title="Tropical climate">
        tropical climate
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-120">
        <a href="#cite_note-120">
         [120]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Snow" title="Snow">
        Snow
       </a>
       falls frequently on the highlands near the east coast, in the states of
       <a href="/wiki/Victoria_(Australia)" title="Victoria (Australia)">
        Victoria
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/New_South_Wales" title="New South Wales">
        New South Wales
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Tasmania" title="Tasmania">
        Tasmania
       </a>
       and in the
       <a href="/wiki/Australian_Capital_Territory" title="Australian Capital Territory">
        Australian Capital Territory
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-121">
        <a href="#cite_note-121">
         [121]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       Most regions of
       <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand" title="New Zealand">
        New Zealand
       </a>
       belong to the temperate zone with a
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Maritime_climate" title="Maritime climate">
        maritime climate
       </a>
       (
       <a href="/wiki/K%C3%B6ppen_climate_classification" title="Köppen climate classification">
        Köppen climate classification
       </a>
       : Cfb) characterised by four distinct seasons. Conditions vary from extremely wet on the
       <a href="/wiki/West_Coast,_New_Zealand" title="West Coast, New Zealand">
        West Coast
       </a>
       of the
       <a href="/wiki/South_Island" title="South Island">
        South Island
       </a>
       to almost
       <a href="/wiki/Semi-arid_climate" title="Semi-arid climate">
        semi-arid
       </a>
       in
       <a href="/wiki/Central_Otago" title="Central Otago">
        Central Otago
       </a>
       and
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Subtropical" title="Subtropical">
        subtropical
       </a>
       in
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/North_Auckland_Peninsula" title="North Auckland Peninsula">
        Northland
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-122">
        <a href="#cite_note-122">
         [122]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-123">
        <a href="#cite_note-123">
         [123]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Snow falls in New Zealand's
       <a href="/wiki/South_Island" title="South Island">
        South Island
       </a>
       and at higher altitudes in the
       <a href="/wiki/North_Island" title="North Island">
        North Island
       </a>
       . It is extremely rare at sea level in the North Island.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-124">
        <a href="#cite_note-124">
         [124]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       Hawaii, although being in the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Tropic" title="Tropic">
        tropics
       </a>
       , experiences many different climates, depending on latitude and its geography. The
       <a href="/wiki/Hawaii_(island)" title="Hawaii (island)">
        island of Hawaii
       </a>
       for example hosts 4 (out of 5 in total) climate groups on a surface as small as 4,028 square miles (10,430 km
       <sup>
        2
       </sup>
       ) according to the
       <a href="/wiki/K%C3%B6ppen_climate_classification" title="Köppen climate classification">
        Köppen climate types
       </a>
       : tropical, arid, temperate and polar. The Hawaiian Islands receive most of their precipitation during the winter months (October to April).
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-125">
        <a href="#cite_note-125">
         [125]
        </a>
       </sup>
       A few islands in the northwest, such as
       <a href="/wiki/Guam" title="Guam">
        Guam
       </a>
       , are susceptible to
       <a href="/wiki/Typhoon" title="Typhoon">
        typhoons
       </a>
       in the wet season.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-126">
        <a href="#cite_note-126">
         [126]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       The highest recorded temperature in Oceania occurred in
       <a href="/wiki/Oodnadatta" title="Oodnadatta">
        Oodnadatta
       </a>
       , South Australia (2 January 1960), where the temperature reached 50.7 °C (123.3 °F).
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-127">
        <a href="#cite_note-127">
         [127]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The lowest temperature ever recorded in Oceania was −25.6 °C (−14.1 °F), at
       <a href="/wiki/Ranfurly,_New_Zealand" title="Ranfurly, New Zealand">
        Ranfurly
       </a>
       in Otago in 1903, with a more recent temperature of −21.6 °C (−6.9 °F) recorded in 1995 in nearby
       <a href="/wiki/Ophir,_New_Zealand" title="Ophir, New Zealand">
        Ophir
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-128">
        <a href="#cite_note-128">
         [128]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Pohnpei" title="Pohnpei">
        Pohnpei
       </a>
       of the
       <a href="/wiki/Senyavin_Islands" title="Senyavin Islands">
        Senyavin Islands
       </a>
       in
       <a href="/wiki/Micronesia" title="Micronesia">
        Micronesia
       </a>
       is the wettest place in Oceania, and one of the wettest places on earth, with annual recorded rainfall exceeding 7,600 millimetres (300 in) each year in certain mountainous locations.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-129">
        <a href="#cite_note-129">
         [129]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The summit of
       <a href="/wiki/Mount_Waialeale" title="Mount Waialeale">
        Mount Waialeale
       </a>
       received 460.0 inches (11,684 mm) in the 1912–45 averages.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-130">
        <a href="#cite_note-130">
         [130]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-131">
        <a href="#cite_note-131">
         [131]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <table style="background:transparent;margin-top:0.5em;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto">
       <tr>
        <th style="text-align:center;font-weight:bold">
         Köppen climate classification of selected regions in Oceania
        </th>
       </tr>
       <tr>
        <td>
         <table style="width:240px;float:left;border-collapse:collapse;margin:3px">
          <tr>
           <td style="height:220px;border:1px solid #CCCCCC;background-color:#F8F8F8;padding:0px;text-align:center">
            <div class="center">
             <div class="floatnone">
              <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Australia_koppen.svg" title="Australia">

      <h2>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Demographics">
        Demographics
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=16" title="Edit section: Demographics">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h2>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       Main article:
       <a href="/wiki/Demographics_of_Oceania" title="Demographics of Oceania">
        Demographics of Oceania
       </a>
      </div>
      <p>
       The linked map below shows the
       <a href="/wiki/Exclusive_economic_zone" title="Exclusive economic zone">
        Exclusive economic zones
       </a>
       (EEZs) of the islands of Oceania and neighbouring areas, as a guide to the following table. (There are no political boundaries that can be drawn on a map of the Pacific at this scale.)
      </p>

       The demographic table below shows the subregions and countries of geopolitical Oceania. The countries and territories in this table are categorised according to the scheme for geographic subregions used by the United Nations. The information shown follows sources in cross-referenced articles; where sources differ, provisos have been clearly indicated. These territories and regions are subject to various additional categorisations, depending on the source and purpose of each description.
      </p>

          </span>
          <span class="reference-text">
           According to Act of Papua Autonomy (Undang-Undang Otonomi Khusus bagi Provinsi Papua) section 2 verse 2, the province itself has their own flag &amp; arms, similar with other provinces. However, the flag &amp; arms is not a representation of sovereignty over Republic of Indonesia
          </span>
         </li>
         <li id="cite_note-138">
          <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
           <b>
            <a href="#cite_ref-138">
             ^
            </a>
           </b>
          </span>
          <span class="reference-text">
           West Papua was split from Papua province in 2003 but still retain the autonomy status as Papua Province
          </span>
         </li>
        </ol>
       </div>
      </div>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Religion">
        Religion
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=17" title="Edit section: Religion">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       Main article:
       <a href="/wiki/Religion_in_Oceania" title="Religion in Oceania">
        Religion in Oceania
       </a>
      </div>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Saione.jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="960" data-file-width="1280" height="165" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/81/Saione.jpg/220px-Saione.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/81/Saione.jpg/330px-Saione.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/81/Saione.jpg/440px-Saione.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Saione.jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         Saione, the church of the King, a
         <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Free_Wesleyan_Church_of_Tonga" title="Free Wesleyan Church of Tonga">
          Free Wesleyan Church
         </a>
         in
         <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Kolomotu%CA%BBa" title="Kolomotuʻa">
          Kolomotuʻa
         </a>
         ,
         <a href="/wiki/Tonga" title="Tonga">
          Tonga
         </a>
         . Due to
         <a href="/wiki/Missionary" title="Missionary">
          missionary
         </a>
         efforts undertaken by various organizations, particularly
         <a href="/wiki/United_Kingdom" title="United Kingdom">
          British
         </a>
         and
         <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">
          American
         </a>
         societies, diverse
         <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Protestant" title="Protestant">
          Protestant
         </a>
         denominations like
         <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Methodist" title="Methodist">
          Methodist
         </a>
         ,
         <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Congregationalist" title="Congregationalist">
          Congregationalist
         </a>
         ,
         <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Baptist" title="Baptist">
          Baptist
         </a>
         ,
         <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Anglican" title="Anglican">
          Anglican
         </a>
         ,
         <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Adventist" title="Adventist">
          Adventist
         </a>
         ,
         <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Pentecostal" title="Pentecostal">
          Pentecostal
         </a>
         ,
         <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Presbyterian" title="Presbyterian">
          Presbyterian
         </a>
         or
         <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/United_Protestant" title="United Protestant">
          United Protestant
         </a>
         churches were introduced throughout Oceania.
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       The predominant religion in Oceania is
       <a href="/wiki/Christianity" title="Christianity">
        Christianity
       </a>
       (73.3%).
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Christianity_in_Oceania_143-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-Christianity_in_Oceania-143">
         [141]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-US_Dept_of_State_Background_Notes_144-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-US_Dept_of_State_Background_Notes-144">
         [142]
        </a>
       </sup>
       A 2011 survey found that 92.1% in
       <a href="/wiki/Melanesia" title="Melanesia">
        Melanesia
       </a>
       ,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Christianity_in_Oceania_143-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-Christianity_in_Oceania-143">
         [141]
        </a>
       </sup>
       93.1% in
       <a href="/wiki/Micronesia" title="Micronesia">
        Micronesia
       </a>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Christianity_in_Oceania_143-2">
        <a href="#cite_note-Christianity_in_Oceania-143">
         [141]
        </a>
       </sup>
       and 96.1% in
       <a href="/wiki/Polynesia" title="Polynesia">
        Polynesia
       </a>
       described themselves as
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Christians" title="Christians">
        Christians
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Christianity_in_Oceania_143-3">
        <a href="#cite_note-Christianity_in_Oceania-143">
         [141]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Traditional religions are often
       <a href="/wiki/Animism" title="Animism">
        animist
       </a>
       , and prevalent among traditional tribes is the belief in spirits (
       <i>
        masalai
       </i>
       in
       <a href="/wiki/Tok_Pisin" title="Tok Pisin">
        Tok Pisin
       </a>
       ) representing natural forces.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Anthropology-Cowan-Messengers_of_the_Gods_145-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-Anthropology-Cowan-Messengers_of_the_Gods-145">
         [143]
        </a>
       </sup>
       In the 2013 census, 47.5% of New Zealanders affiliated themselves with Christianity and 41.92% declared no religion.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-established_146-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-established-146">
         [144]
        </a>
       </sup>
       In the 2016 Census, 52.1% of the Australian population declared some variety of Christianity and 30.1% stated "no religion".
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-147">
        <a href="#cite_note-147">
         [145]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       In recent Australian and New Zealand censuses, large proportions of the population say they belong to "
       <a href="/wiki/Irreligion" title="Irreligion">
        no religion
       </a>
       " (which includes
       <a href="/wiki/Atheism" title="Atheism">
        atheism
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Agnosticism" title="Agnosticism">
        agnosticism
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Deism" title="Deism">
        deism
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Secular_humanism" title="Secular humanism">
        secular humanism
       </a>
       , and
       <a href="/wiki/Rationalism" title="Rationalism">
        rationalism
       </a>
       ). In
       <a href="/wiki/Tonga" title="Tonga">
        Tonga
       </a>
       , everyday life is heavily influenced by
       <a href="/wiki/Polynesian_culture" title="Polynesian culture">
        Polynesian
       </a>
       traditions and especially by the Christian faith. The
       <a href="/wiki/Ahmadiyya" title="Ahmadiyya">
        Ahmadiyya
       </a>
       mosque in Marshall Islands is the only mosque in
       <a href="/wiki/Micronesia" title="Micronesia">
        Micronesia
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-148">
        <a href="#cite_note-148">
         [146]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Another one in
       <a href="/wiki/Tuvalu" title="Tuvalu">
        Tuvalu
       </a>
       belongs to the same sect. The
       <a href="/wiki/Bah%C3%A1%27%C3%AD_House_of_Worship" title="Bahá'í House of Worship">
        Bahá'í House of Worship
       </a>
       in Tiapapata,
       <a href="/wiki/Samoa" title="Samoa">
        Samoa
       </a>
       , is one of seven designations administered in the
       <a href="/wiki/Bah%C3%A1%27%C3%AD_Faith" title="Bahá'í Faith">
        Bahá'í Faith
       </a>
       .
      </p>
      <p>
       Other religions in the region include
       <a href="/wiki/Islam" title="Islam">
        Islam
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Buddhism" title="Buddhism">
        Buddhism
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Hinduism" title="Hinduism">
        Hinduism
       </a>
       , which are prominent
       <a href="/wiki/Minority_religion" title="Minority religion">
        minority religions
       </a>
       in Australia and New Zealand.
       <a href="/wiki/Judaism" title="Judaism">
        Judaism
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Sikhism" title="Sikhism">
        Sikhism
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Jainism" title="Jainism">
        Jainism
       </a>
       are also present. Sir
       <a href="/wiki/Isaac_Isaacs" title="Isaac Isaacs">
        Isaac Isaacs
       </a>
       was the first Australian born
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Governor_General_of_Australia" title="Governor General of Australia">
        Governor General of Australia
       </a>
       and was the first Jewish vice-regal representative in the
       <a href="/wiki/British_Empire" title="British Empire">
        British Empire
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-149">
        <a href="#cite_note-149">
         [147]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Prince_Philip_Movement" title="Prince Philip Movement">
        Prince Philip Movement
       </a>
       is followed around
       <a href="/wiki/Yaohnanen" title="Yaohnanen">
        Yaohnanen
       </a>
       village on the southern island of
       <a href="/wiki/Tanna_(island)" title="Tanna (island)">
        Tanna
       </a>
       in
       <a href="/wiki/Vanuatu" title="Vanuatu">
        Vanuatu
       </a>
       .
      </p>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Languages">
        Languages
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=18" title="Edit section: Languages">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       Main articles:
       <a href="/wiki/Languages_of_Australia" title="Languages of Australia">
        Languages of Australia
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Languages_of_New_Zealand" title="Languages of New Zealand">
        Languages of New Zealand
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Languages_of_Fiji" title="Languages of Fiji">
        Languages of Fiji
       </a>
       , and
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Languages_of_Tonga" title="Languages of Tonga">
        Languages of Tonga
       </a>
      </div>
      <p>
       Native languages of Oceania fall into three major geographic groups:
      </p>
      <ul>
       <li>
        The large
        <a href="/wiki/Austronesian_languages" title="Austronesian languages">
         Austronesian
        </a>
        <a href="/wiki/Language_family" title="Language family">
         language family
        </a>
        , with such languages as
        <a href="/wiki/Malay_language" title="Malay language">
         Malay
        </a>
        (Indonesian), and
        <a href="/wiki/Polynesian_languages" title="Polynesian languages">
         Polynesian languages
        </a>
        such as
        <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Maori_language" title="Maori language">
         Maori
        </a>
        and
        <a href="/wiki/Hawaiian_language" title="Hawaiian language">
         Hawaiian
        </a>
       </li>
       <li>
        The
        <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Aboriginal_Australian_languages" title="Aboriginal Australian languages">
         Aboriginal Australian languages
        </a>
        , including the large
        <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Pama%E2%80%93Nyungan" title="Pama–Nyungan">
         Pama–Nyungan
        </a>
        family
       </li>
       <li>
        The
        <a href="/wiki/Papuan_languages" title="Papuan languages">
         Papuan languages
        </a>
        of
        <a href="/wiki/New_Guinea" title="New Guinea">
         New Guinea
        </a>
        and neighbouring islands, including the large
        <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Trans%E2%80%93New_Guinea" title="Trans–New Guinea">
         Trans–New Guinea
        </a>
        family
       </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
       Colonial languages include
       <a href="/wiki/English_language" title="English language">
        English
       </a>
       in
       <a href="/wiki/Australia" title="Australia">
        Australia
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand" title="New Zealand">
        New Zealand
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Hawaii" title="Hawaii">
        Hawaii
       </a>
       , and many other territories;
       <a href="/wiki/French_language" title="French language">
        French
       </a>
       in
       <a href="/wiki/New_Caledonia" title="New Caledonia">
        New Caledonia
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/French_Polynesia" title="French Polynesia">
        French Polynesia
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Japanese_language" title="Japanese language">
        Japanese
       </a>
       in the
       <a href="/wiki/Bonin_Islands" title="Bonin Islands">
        Bonin Islands
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Spanish_language" title="Spanish language">
        Spanish
       </a>
       on
       <a href="/wiki/Easter_Island" title="Easter Island">
        Easter Island
       </a>
       . There are also
       <a href="/wiki/Creole_language" title="Creole language">
        Creoles
       </a>
       formed from the interaction of Malay or the colonial languages with indigenous languages, such as
       <a href="/wiki/Tok_Pisin" title="Tok Pisin">
        Tok Pisin
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Bislama" title="Bislama">
        Bislama
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Chavacano" title="Chavacano">
        Chavacano
       </a>
       , various
       <a href="/wiki/Malay_trade_and_creole_languages" title="Malay trade and creole languages">
        Malay trade and creole languages
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Hawaiian_Pidgin" title="Hawaiian Pidgin">
        Hawaiian Pidgin
       </a>
       ,
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Norfuk" title="Norfuk">
        Norfuk
       </a>
       , and
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Pitkern" title="Pitkern">
        Pitkern
       </a>
       . Contact between Austronesian and Papuan resulted in several instances in mixed languages such as
       <a href="/wiki/Maisin_language" title="Maisin language">
        Maisin
       </a>
       .
      </p>
      <p>
       Immigrants brought their own languages to the region, such as
       <a href="/wiki/Standard_Chinese" title="Standard Chinese">
        Mandarin
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Italian_language" title="Italian language">
        Italian
       </a>
       ,
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Arabic_language" title="Arabic language">
        Arabic
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Polish_language" title="Polish language">
        Polish
       </a>
       ,
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Hindi_language" title="Hindi language">
        Hindi
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/German_language" title="German language">
        German
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Spanish_language" title="Spanish language">
        Spanish
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Korean_language" title="Korean language">
        Korean
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Cantonese" title="Cantonese">
        Cantonese
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Greek_language" title="Greek language">
        Greek
       </a>
       , among others, namely in Australia and New Zealand,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-150">
        <a href="#cite_note-150">
         [148]
        </a>
       </sup>
       or
       <a href="/wiki/Fiji_Hindi" title="Fiji Hindi">
        Fiji Hindi
       </a>
       in
       <a href="/wiki/Fiji" title="Fiji">
        Fiji
       </a>
       .
      </p>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Immigration">
        Immigration
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=19" title="Edit section: Immigration">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       Main articles:
       <a href="/wiki/Post-war_immigration_to_Australia" title="Post-war immigration to Australia">
        Post-war immigration to Australia
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Immigration_to_Australia" title="Immigration to Australia">
        Immigration to Australia
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Immigration_to_New_Zealand" title="Immigration to New Zealand">
        Immigration to New Zealand
       </a>
       ,
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Refugees_in_Australia" title="Refugees in Australia">
        Refugees in Australia
       </a>
       , and
       <a href="/wiki/Refugees_in_New_Zealand" title="Refugees in New Zealand">
        Refugees in New Zealand
       </a>
      </div>
      <div class="thumb tleft">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Dutch_Migrant_1954_MariaScholte%3D50000thToAustraliaPostWW2.jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="343" data-file-width="450" height="168" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9d/Dutch_Migrant_1954_MariaScholte%3D50000thToAustraliaPostWW2.jpg/220px-Dutch_Migrant_1954_MariaScholte%3D50000thToAustraliaPostWW2.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9d/Dutch_Migrant_1954_MariaScholte%3D50000thToAustraliaPostWW2.jpg/330px-Dutch_Migrant_1954_MariaScholte%3D50000thToAustraliaPostWW2.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9d/Dutch_Migrant_1954_MariaScholte%3D50000thToAustraliaPostWW2.jpg/440px-Dutch_Migrant_1954_MariaScholte%3D50000thToAustraliaPostWW2.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Dutch_Migrant_1954_MariaScholte%3D50000thToAustraliaPostWW2.jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         <a href="/wiki/Dutch_Australians" title="Dutch Australians">
          Dutch
         </a>
         immigrants arriving in Australia (1954).
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       The most multicultural areas in Oceania, which have a
       <a href="/wiki/List_of_sovereign_states_and_dependent_territories_by_immigrant_population" title="List of sovereign states and dependent territories by immigrant population">
        high degree
       </a>
       of
       <a href="/wiki/Immigration" title="Immigration">
        immigration
       </a>
       , are Australia, New Zealand and Hawaii. Since 1945, more than 7 million people have settled in Australia. From the late 1970s, there was a significant increase in immigration from Asian and other non-European countries, making Australia a
       <a href="/wiki/Multiculturalism_in_Australia" title="Multiculturalism in Australia">
        multicultural country
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-151">
        <a href="#cite_note-151">
         [149]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       Sydney is the most
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Multicultural" title="Multicultural">
        multicultural
       </a>
       city in Oceania, having more than 250 different languages spoken with about 40 percent of residents speaking a
       <a href="/wiki/Languages_Other_Than_English" title="Languages Other Than English">
        language other than English
       </a>
       at home.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-152">
        <a href="#cite_note-152">
         [150]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Furthermore, 36 percent of the population reported having been
       <a href="/wiki/Foreign_born" title="Foreign born">
        born overseas
       </a>
       , with top countries being
       <a href="/wiki/Italy" title="Italy">
        Italy
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Lebanon" title="Lebanon">
        Lebanon
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Vietnam" title="Vietnam">
        Vietnam
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Iraq" title="Iraq">
        Iraq
       </a>
       , among others.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-TheAus_153-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-TheAus-153">
         [151]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Population,_dwellings,_and_ethnicity_154-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-Population,_dwellings,_and_ethnicity-154">
         [152]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Melbourne" title="Melbourne">
        Melbourne
       </a>
       is also fairly multicultural, having the largest
       <a href="/wiki/Greek_community_of_Melbourne" title="Greek community of Melbourne">
        Greek-speaking
       </a>
       population outside of
       <a href="/wiki/Europe" title="Europe">
        Europe
       </a>
       ,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-155">
        <a href="#cite_note-155">
         [153]
        </a>
       </sup>
       and the second largest
       <a href="/wiki/Asian_Australians" title="Asian Australians">
        Asian
       </a>
       population in Australia after Sydney.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-156">
        <a href="#cite_note-156">
         [154]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-157">
        <a href="#cite_note-157">
         [155]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-158">
        <a href="#cite_note-158">
         [156]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       European migration to New Zealand provided a major influx following the signing of the
       <a href="/wiki/Treaty_of_Waitangi" title="Treaty of Waitangi">
        Treaty of Waitangi
       </a>
       in 1840. Subsequent immigration has been chiefly from the British Isles, but also from continental Europe, the Pacific, The Americas and Asia.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-159">
        <a href="#cite_note-159">
         [157]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-160">
        <a href="#cite_note-160">
         [158]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Auckland" title="Auckland">
        Auckland
       </a>
       is home to over half (51.6 percent) of New Zealand's overseas born population, including 72 percent of the country's Pacific Island-born population, 64 percent of its
       <a href="/wiki/Asian_people" title="Asian people">
        Asian
       </a>
       -born population, and 56 percent of its
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Middle_Eastern_people" title="Middle Eastern people">
        Middle Eastern
       </a>
       and
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/African_people" title="African people">
        African
       </a>
       born population.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-161">
        <a href="#cite_note-161">
         [159]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Portuguese_immigrant_family_in_Hawaii_during_the_19th_century.jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="500" data-file-width="629" height="175" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/Portuguese_immigrant_family_in_Hawaii_during_the_19th_century.jpg/220px-Portuguese_immigrant_family_in_Hawaii_during_the_19th_century.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/Portuguese_immigrant_family_in_Hawaii_during_the_19th_century.jpg/330px-Portuguese_immigrant_family_in_Hawaii_during_the_19th_century.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/Portuguese_immigrant_family_in_Hawaii_during_the_19th_century.jpg/440px-Portuguese_immigrant_family_in_Hawaii_during_the_19th_century.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Portuguese_immigrant_family_in_Hawaii_during_the_19th_century.jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         Many
         <a href="/wiki/Portuguese_Americans" title="Portuguese Americans">
          Portuguese
         </a>
         immigrants in Hawaii were
         <a href="/wiki/Azores" title="Azores">
          Azorean
         </a>
         or
         <a href="/wiki/Madeira" title="Madeira">
          Madeiran
