         </a>
         .
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       Hawaii is a
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Majority-minority_state" title="Majority-minority state">
        majority-minority state
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-162">
        <a href="#cite_note-162">
         [160]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Chinese_people" title="Chinese people">
        Chinese
       </a>
       workers on Western trading ships settled in Hawaii starting in 1789. In 1820, the first American missionaries arrived to preach Christianity and teach the Hawaiians Western ways.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Charles_Williams_163-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-Charles_Williams-163">
         [161]
        </a>
       </sup>
       As of 2015
       <sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
        <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit">
         [update]
        </a>
       </sup>
       , a large proportion of Hawaii's population have Asian ancestry—especially
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Filipino_people" title="Filipino people">
        Filipino
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Japanese_people" title="Japanese people">
        Japanese
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Korean_immigration_to_Hawaii" title="Korean immigration to Hawaii">
        Korean
       </a>
       and Chinese. Many are descendants of immigrants brought to work on the sugarcane plantations in the mid-to-late 19th century. Almost 13,000
       <a href="/wiki/Portuguese_people" title="Portuguese people">
        Portuguese
       </a>
       immigrants had arrived by 1899; they also worked on the
       <a href="/wiki/Sugarcane" title="Sugarcane">
        sugarcane
       </a>
       plantations.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Hoffman_164-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-Hoffman-164">
         [162]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Puerto_Rican_immigration_to_Hawaii" title="Puerto Rican immigration to Hawaii">
        Puerto Rican immigration to Hawaii
       </a>
       began in 1899 when Puerto Rico's sugar industry was devastated by two hurricanes, causing a worldwide shortage of sugar and a huge demand for sugar from Hawaii.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-165">
        <a href="#cite_note-165">
         [163]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       Between 2001 and 2007 Australia's
       <a href="/wiki/Pacific_Solution" title="Pacific Solution">
        Pacific Solution
       </a>
       policy transferred
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Asylum_seekers" title="Asylum seekers">
        asylum seekers
       </a>
       to several Pacific nations, including the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Nauru_detention_centre" title="Nauru detention centre">
        Nauru detention centre
       </a>
       . Australia, New Zealand and other nations took part in the
       <a href="/wiki/Regional_Assistance_Mission_to_Solomon_Islands" title="Regional Assistance Mission to Solomon Islands">
        Regional Assistance Mission to Solomon Islands
       </a>
       from 2003 after a request for aid.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-bat_166-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-bat-166">
         [164]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Archaeogenetics">
        Archaeogenetics
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=20" title="Edit section: Archaeogenetics">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <p>
       <a href="/wiki/Archaeology" title="Archaeology">
        Archaeology
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Linguistics" title="Linguistics">
        linguistics
       </a>
       , and existing
       <a href="/wiki/Genetics" title="Genetics">
        genetic studies
       </a>
       indicate that Oceania was settled by two major waves of migration. The first migration took place approximately 40 thousand years ago, and these migrants,
       <a href="/wiki/Papuan_people" title="Papuan people">
        Papuans
       </a>
       , colonised much of
       <a href="/wiki/Near_Oceania" title="Near Oceania">
        Near Oceania
       </a>
       . Approximately 3.5 thousand years ago, a second expansion of
       <a href="/wiki/Austronesian_languages" title="Austronesian languages">
        Austronesian
       </a>
       speakers arrived in Near Oceania, and the descendants of these people spread to the far corners of the Pacific, colonising
       <a href="/wiki/Remote_Oceania" title="Remote Oceania">
        Remote Oceania
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-doi10.1016/j.ajhg.2014.03.014_167-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-doi10.1016/j.ajhg.2014.03.014-167">
         [165]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       <a href="/wiki/Mitochondrial_DNA" title="Mitochondrial DNA">
        Mitochondrial DNA
       </a>
       (mtDNA) studies quantify the magnitude of the
       <a href="/wiki/Austronesian_peoples" title="Austronesian peoples">
        Austronesian expansion
       </a>
       and demonstrate the homogenising effect of this expansion. With regards to Papuan influence, autochthonous
       <a href="/wiki/Haplogroup" title="Haplogroup">
        haplogroups
       </a>
       support the hypothesis of a long history in Near Oceania, with some lineages suggesting a time depth of 60 thousand years.
       <a href="/wiki/Santa_Cruz_Islands" title="Santa Cruz Islands">
        Santa Cruz
       </a>
       , a population located in Remote Oceania, is an anomaly with extreme frequencies of autochthonous haplogroups of Near Oceanian origin.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-doi10.1016/j.ajhg.2014.03.014_167-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-doi10.1016/j.ajhg.2014.03.014-167">
         [165]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       Large areas of
       <a href="/wiki/New_Guinea" title="New Guinea">
        New Guinea
       </a>
       are unexplored by scientists and
       <a href="/wiki/Anthropologist" title="Anthropologist">
        anthropologists
       </a>
       due to extensive
       <a href="/wiki/Forestation" title="Forestation">
        forestation
       </a>
       and mountainous terrain. Known indigenous tribes in
       <a href="/wiki/Papua_New_Guinea" title="Papua New Guinea">
        Papua New Guinea
       </a>
       have very little contact with local authorities aside from the authorities knowing who they are. Many remain
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Preliterate" title="Preliterate">
        preliterate
       </a>
       and, at the national or international level, the names of tribes and information about them is extremely hard to obtain. The
       <a href="/wiki/Indonesia" title="Indonesia">
        Indonesian
       </a>
       provinces of
       <a href="/wiki/Papua_(province)" title="Papua (province)">
        Papua
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/West_Papua_(province)" title="West Papua (province)">
        West Papua
       </a>
       on the island of New Guinea are home to an estimated 44
       <a href="/wiki/Uncontacted_peoples" title="Uncontacted peoples">
        uncontacted tribal groups
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-168">
        <a href="#cite_note-168">
         [166]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h2>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Economy">
        Economy
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=21" title="Edit section: Economy">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h2>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       Main article:
       <a href="/wiki/Economy_of_Oceania" title="Economy of Oceania">
        Economy of Oceania
       </a>
      </div>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Australia_and_New_Zealand">
        Australia and New Zealand
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=22" title="Edit section: Australia and New Zealand">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       Main articles:
       <a href="/wiki/Economy_of_Australia" title="Economy of Australia">
        Economy of Australia
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Economy_of_New_Zealand" title="Economy of New Zealand">
        Economy of New Zealand
       </a>
      </div>
      <div class="thumb tleft">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:252px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Sydney_skyline_from_Waverton_Balls_head_reserve.jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="4912" data-file-width="7008" height="175" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/13/Sydney_skyline_from_Waverton_Balls_head_reserve.jpg/250px-Sydney_skyline_from_Waverton_Balls_head_reserve.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/13/Sydney_skyline_from_Waverton_Balls_head_reserve.jpg/375px-Sydney_skyline_from_Waverton_Balls_head_reserve.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/13/Sydney_skyline_from_Waverton_Balls_head_reserve.jpg/500px-Sydney_skyline_from_Waverton_Balls_head_reserve.jpg 2x" width="250"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Sydney_skyline_from_Waverton_Balls_head_reserve.jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         The
         <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Skyline_of_Sydney" title="Skyline of Sydney">
          skyline of Sydney
         </a>
         .
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand" title="New Zealand">
        New Zealand
       </a>
       and Australia are the only
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/First_world" title="First world">
        first world
       </a>
       nations in the region, although the
       <a href="/wiki/Economy_of_Australia" title="Economy of Australia">
        economy of Australia
       </a>
       is by far the largest and most dominant economy in the region and one of the largest in the world. Australia's per-capita GDP is
       <a href="/wiki/List_of_countries_by_GDP_(PPP)_per_capita" title="List of countries by GDP (PPP) per capita">
        higher
       </a>
       than that of the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/UK" title="UK">
        UK
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Canada" title="Canada">
        Canada
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Germany" title="Germany">
        Germany
       </a>
       , and
       <a href="/wiki/France" title="France">
        France
       </a>
       in terms of
       <a href="/wiki/Purchasing_power_parity" title="Purchasing power parity">
        purchasing power parity
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-169">
        <a href="#cite_note-169">
         [167]
        </a>
       </sup>
       New Zealand is also one of the most globalised economies and depends greatly on international trade.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-170">
        <a href="#cite_note-170">
         [168]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-171">
        <a href="#cite_note-171">
         [169]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       The
       <a href="/wiki/Australian_Securities_Exchange" title="Australian Securities Exchange">
        Australian Securities Exchange
       </a>
       in
       <a href="/wiki/Sydney" title="Sydney">
        Sydney
       </a>
       is the largest
       <a href="/wiki/List_of_stock_exchanges_in_Oceania" title="List of stock exchanges in Oceania">
        stock exchange in Australia and in the South Pacific
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-172">
        <a href="#cite_note-172">
         [170]
        </a>
       </sup>
       New Zealand is the
       <a href="/wiki/List_of_countries_by_GDP_(nominal)" title="List of countries by GDP (nominal)">
        53rd
       </a>
       -largest national economy in the world measured by
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Nominal_gross_domestic_product" title="Nominal gross domestic product">
        nominal gross domestic product
       </a>
       (GDP) and
       <a href="/wiki/List_of_countries_by_GDP_(PPP)" title="List of countries by GDP (PPP)">
        68th
       </a>
       -largest in the world measured by
       <a href="/wiki/Purchasing_power_parity" title="Purchasing power parity">
        purchasing power parity
       </a>
       (PPP). In 2012, Australia was the 12th largest national economy by nominal GDP and the 19th-largest measured by
       <a href="/wiki/Purchasing_power_parity" title="Purchasing power parity">
        PPP-adjusted
       </a>
       GDP.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-173">
        <a href="#cite_note-173">
         [171]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       <a href="/wiki/Mercer_Quality_of_Living_Survey" title="Mercer Quality of Living Survey">
        Mercer Quality of Living Survey
       </a>
       ranks Sydney tenth in the world in terms of
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Quality_of_living" title="Quality of living">
        quality of living
       </a>
       ,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-mercer.com_174-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-mercer.com-174">
         [172]
        </a>
       </sup>
       making it one of the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/World%27s_most_livable_cities" title="World's most livable cities">
        most livable cities
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-175">
        <a href="#cite_note-175">
         [173]
        </a>
       </sup>
       It is classified as an Alpha+
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/World_City" title="World City">
        World City
       </a>
       by
       <a href="/wiki/Globalization_and_World_Cities_Research_Network" title="Globalization and World Cities Research Network">
        GaWC
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-176">
        <a href="#cite_note-176">
         [174]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-177">
        <a href="#cite_note-177">
         [175]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Melbourne" title="Melbourne">
        Melbourne
       </a>
       also ranked highly in the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/World%27s_Most_Livable_Cities" title="World's Most Livable Cities">
        world's most liveable city
       </a>
       list,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-178">
        <a href="#cite_note-178">
         [176]
        </a>
       </sup>
       and is a leading
       <a href="/wiki/Financial_centre" title="Financial centre">
        financial centre
       </a>
       in the
       <a href="/wiki/Asia-Pacific" title="Asia-Pacific">
        Asia-Pacific
       </a>
       region.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-179">
        <a href="#cite_note-179">
         [177]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-180">
        <a href="#cite_note-180">
         [178]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Auckland and
       <a href="/wiki/Wellington" title="Wellington">
        Wellington
       </a>
       , in New Zealand, are frequently ranked among the
       <a href="/wiki/World%27s_most_liveable_cities" title="World's most liveable cities">
        world's most liveable cities
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-181">
        <a href="#cite_note-181">
         [179]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-182">
        <a href="#cite_note-182">
         [180]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       The majority of people living in Australia and to a lesser extent, New Zealand work in
       <a href="/wiki/Mining_in_Australia" title="Mining in Australia">
        mining
       </a>
       , electrical and
       <a href="/wiki/Manufacturing_in_Australia" title="Manufacturing in Australia">
        manufacturing
       </a>
       sectors also. Australia boasts the largest amount of manufacturing in the region,
       <a href="/wiki/Automotive_industry_in_Australia" title="Automotive industry in Australia">
        producing cars
       </a>
       , electrical equipment, machinery and
       <a href="/wiki/Clothing_industry" title="Clothing industry">
        clothes
       </a>
       .
      </p>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Pacific_Islands">
        Pacific Islands
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=23" title="Edit section: Pacific Islands">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       Main articles:
       <a href="/wiki/Economy_of_Fiji" title="Economy of Fiji">
        Economy of Fiji
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Economy_of_Samoa" title="Economy of Samoa">
        Economy of Samoa
       </a>
       , and
       <a href="/wiki/Economy_of_Tonga" title="Economy of Tonga">
        Economy of Tonga
       </a>
      </div>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:252px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Waikiki_view_from_Diamond_Head.JPG">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="1129" data-file-width="2000" height="141" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/21/Waikiki_view_from_Diamond_Head.JPG/250px-Waikiki_view_from_Diamond_Head.JPG" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/21/Waikiki_view_from_Diamond_Head.JPG/375px-Waikiki_view_from_Diamond_Head.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/21/Waikiki_view_from_Diamond_Head.JPG/500px-Waikiki_view_from_Diamond_Head.JPG 2x" width="250"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Waikiki_view_from_Diamond_Head.JPG" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         <a href="/wiki/Honolulu" title="Honolulu">
          Honolulu
         </a>
         viewed from
         <a href="/wiki/Diamond_Head,_Hawaii" title="Diamond Head, Hawaii">
          Diamond Head
         </a>
         crater
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       The overwhelming majority of people living in the Pacific islands work in the service industry which includes tourism, education and financial services. Oceania's largest export markets include
       <a href="/wiki/Japan" title="Japan">
        Japan
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/China" title="China">
        China
       </a>
       , the United States and
       <a href="/wiki/South_Korea" title="South Korea">
        South Korea
       </a>
       . The smallest
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Pacific" title="Pacific">
        Pacific
       </a>
       nations rely on trade with Australia, New Zealand and the United States for exporting goods and for accessing other products. Australia and New Zealand's trading arrangements are known as
       <a href="/wiki/Closer_Economic_Relations" title="Closer Economic Relations">
        Closer Economic Relations
       </a>
       . Australia and New Zealand, along with other countries, are members of
       <a href="/wiki/Asia-Pacific_Economic_Cooperation" title="Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation">
        Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation
       </a>
       (APEC) and the
       <a href="/wiki/East_Asia_Summit" title="East Asia Summit">
        East Asia Summit
       </a>
       (EAS), which may become trade blocs in the future particularly EAS.
      </p>
      <p>
       The main produce from the pacific is
       <a href="/wiki/Copra" title="Copra">
        copra
       </a>
       or
       <a href="/wiki/Coconut" title="Coconut">
        coconut
       </a>
       , but
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Timber" title="Timber">
        timber
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Beef" title="Beef">
        beef
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Palm_oil" title="Palm oil">
        palm oil
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Cocoa_bean" title="Cocoa bean">
        cocoa
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Sugar" title="Sugar">
        sugar
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Ginger" title="Ginger">
        ginger
       </a>
       are also commonly grown across the
       <a href="/wiki/Tropics" title="Tropics">
        tropics
       </a>
       of the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Pacific" title="Pacific">
        Pacific
       </a>
       .
       <a href="/wiki/Fishing" title="Fishing">
        Fishing
       </a>
       provides a major
       <a href="/wiki/Industry" title="Industry">
        industry
       </a>
       for many of the smaller nations in the
       <a href="/wiki/Pacific_Ocean" title="Pacific Ocean">
        Pacific
       </a>
       , although many
       <a href="/wiki/Fishing" title="Fishing">
        fishing
       </a>
       areas are exploited by other larger countries, namely Japan.
       <a href="/wiki/Natural_Resources" title="Natural Resources">
        Natural Resources
       </a>
       , such as
       <a href="/wiki/Lead" title="Lead">
        lead
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Zinc" title="Zinc">
        zinc
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Nickel" title="Nickel">
        nickel
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Gold" title="Gold">
        gold
       </a>
       , are mined in Australia and the
       <a href="/wiki/Solomon_Islands" title="Solomon Islands">
        Solomon Islands
       </a>
       . Oceania's largest export markets include Japan, China, the United States, India, South Korea and the
       <a href="/wiki/European_Union" title="European Union">
        European Union
       </a>
       .
      </p>
      <p>
       Endowed with
       <a href="/wiki/Forest" title="Forest">
        forest
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Mineral" title="Mineral">
        mineral
       </a>
       , and
       <a href="/wiki/Fish" title="Fish">
        fish
       </a>
       resources,
       <a href="/wiki/Fiji" title="Fiji">
        Fiji
       </a>
       is one of the most developed of the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Pacific_island" title="Pacific island">
        Pacific island
       </a>
       <a href="/wiki/Economics" title="Economics">
        economies
       </a>
       , though it remains a
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Developing_nation" title="Developing nation">
        developing country
       </a>
       with a large
       <a href="/wiki/Subsistence_agriculture" title="Subsistence agriculture">
        subsistence agriculture
       </a>
       sector.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-183">
        <a href="#cite_note-183">
         [181]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Agriculture accounts for 18% of
       <a href="/wiki/Gross_domestic_product" title="Gross domestic product">
        gross domestic product
       </a>
       , although it employed some 70% of the workforce as of 2001.
       <a href="/wiki/Sugar" title="Sugar">
        Sugar
       </a>
       exports and the growing tourist industry are the major sources of foreign exchange. Sugar cane processing makes up one-third of industrial activity.
       <a href="/wiki/Coconut" title="Coconut">
        Coconuts
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Ginger" title="Ginger">
        ginger
       </a>
       , and
       <a href="/wiki/Copra" title="Copra">
        copra
       </a>
       are also significant.
      </p>
      <p>
       The history of Hawaii's economy can be traced through a succession of dominant industries;
       <a href="/wiki/Sandalwood" title="Sandalwood">
        sandalwood
       </a>
       ,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-184">
        <a href="#cite_note-184">
         [182]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Whaling" title="Whaling">
        whaling
       </a>
       ,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-185">
        <a href="#cite_note-185">
         [183]
        </a>
       </sup>
       sugarcane,
       <a href="/wiki/Pineapple" title="Pineapple">
        pineapple
       </a>
       , the military, tourism and education.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-186">
        <a href="#cite_note-186">
         [184]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Hawaiian exports include food and clothing. These industries play a small role in the Hawaiian economy, due to the shipping distance to viable markets, such as the West Coast of the contiguous U.S. The state's food exports include coffee, macadamia nuts, pineapple, livestock, sugarcane and honey.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-187">
        <a href="#cite_note-187">
         [185]
        </a>
       </sup>
       As of 2015
       <sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">
        <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit">
         [update]
        </a>
       </sup>
       , Honolulu was ranked high on world livability rankings, and was also ranked as the 2nd safest city in the U.S.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-MercerSurvey2015_188-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-MercerSurvey2015-188">
         [186]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-KITVSafestCity_189-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-KITVSafestCity-189">
         [187]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Tourism">
        Tourism
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=24" title="Edit section: Tourism">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <div class="thumb tleft">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Shangri-La_Fijian_Resort_15.jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="3456" data-file-width="5184" height="147" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/Shangri-La_Fijian_Resort_15.jpg/220px-Shangri-La_Fijian_Resort_15.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/Shangri-La_Fijian_Resort_15.jpg/330px-Shangri-La_Fijian_Resort_15.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/Shangri-La_Fijian_Resort_15.jpg/440px-Shangri-La_Fijian_Resort_15.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Shangri-La_Fijian_Resort_15.jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         <a href="/wiki/Shangri-La%27s_Fijian_Resort" title="Shangri-La's Fijian Resort">
          Shangri-La's Fijian Resort
         </a>
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       Tourists mostly come from Japan, the
       <a href="/wiki/United_Kingdom" title="United Kingdom">
        United Kingdom
       </a>
       and the United States.
       <a href="/wiki/Economy_of_Fiji#Tourism" title="Economy of Fiji">
        Fiji
       </a>
       currently draws almost half a million tourists each year; more than a quarter from Australia. This contributes $1 billion or more since 1995 to Fiji's economy but the Government of Fiji islands underestimate these figures due to invisible economy inside tourism industry.
      </p>
      <p>
       Vanuatu is widely recognised as one of the premier vacation destinations for
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Scuba_diver" title="Scuba diver">
        scuba divers
       </a>
       wishing to explore
       <a href="/wiki/Coral_reef" title="Coral reef">
        coral reefs
       </a>
       of the South Pacific region. Tourism has been promoted, in part, by Vanuatu being the site of several reality-TV shows. The ninth season of the reality TV series
       <i>
        <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Survivor_(US_TV_series)" title="Survivor (US TV series)">
         Survivor
        </a>
       </i>
       was filmed on Vanuatu, entitled
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Survivor:_Vanuatu" title="Survivor: Vanuatu">
         Survivor: Vanuatu
        </a>
        —Islands of Fire
       </i>
       . Two years later, Australia's
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Celebrity_Survivor" title="Celebrity Survivor">
         Celebrity Survivor
        </a>
       </i>
       was filmed at the same location used by the US version.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-190">
        <a href="#cite_note-190">
         [188]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Autumn_in_the_Dandenong_Ranges.jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="2848" data-file-width="4288" height="146" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/83/Autumn_in_the_Dandenong_Ranges.jpg/220px-Autumn_in_the_Dandenong_Ranges.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/83/Autumn_in_the_Dandenong_Ranges.jpg/330px-Autumn_in_the_Dandenong_Ranges.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/83/Autumn_in_the_Dandenong_Ranges.jpg/440px-Autumn_in_the_Dandenong_Ranges.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Autumn_in_the_Dandenong_Ranges.jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         <a href="/wiki/Dandenong_Ranges" title="Dandenong Ranges">
          Dandenong Ranges
         </a>
         in
         <a href="/wiki/Victoria_(Australia)" title="Victoria (Australia)">
          Victoria
         </a>
         are popular among tourists.
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       <a href="/wiki/Tourism_in_Australia" title="Tourism in Australia">
        Tourism in Australia
       </a>
       is an important component of the Australian economy. In the financial year 2014/15,
       <a href="/wiki/Tourism" title="Tourism">
        tourism
       </a>
       represented 3.0% of
       <a href="/wiki/Australia" title="Australia">
        Australia
       </a>
       's
       <a href="/wiki/Gross_domestic_product" title="Gross domestic product">
        GDP
       </a>
       contributing A$47.5 billion to the national economy.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ABS1011_191-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-ABS1011-191">
         [189]
        </a>
       </sup>
       In 2015, there were 7.4 million visitor arrivals.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-192">
        <a href="#cite_note-192">
         [190]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Popular Australian destinations include the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Sydney_Harbour" title="Sydney Harbour">
        Sydney Harbour
       </a>
       (
       <a href="/wiki/Sydney_Opera_House" title="Sydney Opera House">
        Sydney Opera House
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Sydney_Harbour_Bridge" title="Sydney Harbour Bridge">
        Sydney Harbour Bridge
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Royal_Botanic_Garden,_Sydney" title="Royal Botanic Garden, Sydney">
        Royal Botanic Garden
       </a>
       , etc.),
       <a href="/wiki/Gold_Coast,_Queensland" title="Gold Coast, Queensland">
        Gold Coast
       </a>
       (
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Theme_parks" title="Theme parks">
        theme parks
       </a>
       such as
       <a href="/wiki/Warner_Bros._Movie_World" title="Warner Bros. Movie World">
        Warner Bros. Movie World
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Dreamworld" title="Dreamworld">
        Dreamworld
       </a>
       and
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Sea_World" title="Sea World">
        Sea World
       </a>
       ),
       <a href="/wiki/Walls_of_Jerusalem_National_Park" title="Walls of Jerusalem National Park">
        Walls of Jerusalem National Park
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Mount_Field_National_Park" title="Mount Field National Park">
        Mount Field National Park
       </a>
       in
       <a href="/wiki/Tasmania" title="Tasmania">
        Tasmania
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Royal_Exhibition_Building" title="Royal Exhibition Building">
        Royal Exhibition Building
       </a>
       in
       <a href="/wiki/Melbourne" title="Melbourne">
        Melbourne
       </a>
       , the
       <a href="/wiki/Great_Barrier_Reef" title="Great Barrier Reef">
        Great Barrier Reef
       </a>
       in
       <a href="/wiki/Queensland" title="Queensland">
        Queensland
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/The_Twelve_Apostles_(Victoria)" title="The Twelve Apostles (Victoria)">
        The Twelve Apostles
       </a>
       in
       <a href="/wiki/Victoria_(Australia)" title="Victoria (Australia)">
        Victoria
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Uluru" title="Uluru">
        Uluru
       </a>
       and the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Australian_outback" title="Australian outback">
        Australian outback
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-193">
        <a href="#cite_note-193">
         [191]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       <a href="/wiki/Tourism_in_New_Zealand" title="Tourism in New Zealand">
        Tourism in New Zealand
       </a>
       contributes
       <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_dollar" title="New Zealand dollar">
        NZ$
       </a>
       7.3 billion (or 3.7%) of the country's
       <a href="/wiki/Gross_domestic_product" title="Gross domestic product">
        GDP
       </a>
       in 2013, as well as directly supporting 110,800 full-time equivalent jobs (nearly 6% of New Zealand's workforce). International tourist spending accounted for 16% of New Zealand's export earnings (nearly NZ$10 billion). International and domestic tourism contributes, in total, NZ$24 billion to New Zealand's economy every year.
       <a href="/wiki/Tourism_New_Zealand" title="Tourism New Zealand">
        Tourism New Zealand
       </a>
       , the country's official tourism agency, is actively promoting the country as a destination worldwide.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-194">
        <a href="#cite_note-194">
         [192]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Milford_Sound" title="Milford Sound">
        Milford Sound
       </a>
       in
       <a href="/wiki/South_Island" title="South Island">
        South Island
       </a>
       is acclaimed as New Zealand's most famous tourist destination.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-SC_195-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-SC-195">
         [193]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       In 2003 alone, according to state government data, there were over 6.4 million
       <a href="/wiki/Tourism_in_Hawaii" title="Tourism in Hawaii">
        visitors to the Hawaiian Islands
       </a>
       with expenditures of over $10.6 billion.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-DBEDT_2003_196-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-DBEDT_2003-196">
         [194]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Due to the mild year-round weather, tourist travel is popular throughout the year. In 2011, Hawaii saw increasing arrivals and share of foreign tourists from Canada, Australia and China increasing 13%, 24% and 21% respectively from 2010.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-197">
        <a href="#cite_note-197">
         [195]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h2>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Politics">
        Politics
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=25" title="Edit section: Politics">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h2>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Australia_2">
        Australia
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=26" title="Edit section: Australia">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       Main article:
       <a href="/wiki/Politics_of_Australia" title="Politics of Australia">
        Politics of Australia
       </a>
      </div>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:152px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Elizabeth_II_greets_NASA_GSFC_employees,_May_8,_2007_edit.jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="2060" data-file-width="1488" height="208" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5f/Elizabeth_II_greets_NASA_GSFC_employees%2C_May_8%2C_2007_edit.jpg/150px-Elizabeth_II_greets_NASA_GSFC_employees%2C_May_8%2C_2007_edit.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5f/Elizabeth_II_greets_NASA_GSFC_employees%2C_May_8%2C_2007_edit.jpg/225px-Elizabeth_II_greets_NASA_GSFC_employees%2C_May_8%2C_2007_edit.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5f/Elizabeth_II_greets_NASA_GSFC_employees%2C_May_8%2C_2007_edit.jpg/300px-Elizabeth_II_greets_NASA_GSFC_employees%2C_May_8%2C_2007_edit.jpg 2x" width="150"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Elizabeth_II_greets_NASA_GSFC_employees,_May_8,_2007_edit.jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         Elizabeth is
         <a href="/wiki/Head_of_the_Commonwealth" title="Head of the Commonwealth">
          Head of the Commonwealth
         </a>
         and Queen of 5 Oceanian countries:
         <a href="/wiki/Australia" title="Australia">
          Australia
         </a>
         ,
         <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand" title="New Zealand">
          New Zealand
         </a>
         ,
         <a href="/wiki/Papua_New_Guinea" title="Papua New Guinea">
          Papua New Guinea
         </a>
         ,
         <a href="/wiki/Solomon_Islands" title="Solomon Islands">
          Solomon Islands
         </a>
         and
         <a href="/wiki/Tuvalu" title="Tuvalu">
          Tuvalu
         </a>
         .
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       Australia is a
       <a href="/wiki/Federalism" title="Federalism">
        federal
       </a>
       <a href="/wiki/Parliamentary_system" title="Parliamentary system">
        parliamentary
       </a>
       <a href="/wiki/Constitutional_monarchy" title="Constitutional monarchy">
        constitutional monarchy
       </a>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-198">
        <a href="#cite_note-198">
         [196]
        </a>
       </sup>
       with
       <a href="/wiki/Elizabeth_II" title="Elizabeth II">
        Elizabeth II
       </a>
       at its apex as the
       <a href="/wiki/Monarchy_of_Australia" title="Monarchy of Australia">
        Queen of Australia
       </a>
       , a role that is distinct from her position as monarch of the other
       <a href="/wiki/Commonwealth_realm" title="Commonwealth realm">
        Commonwealth realms
       </a>
       . The Queen is represented in Australia by the
       <a href="/wiki/Governor-General_of_Australia" title="Governor-General of Australia">
        Governor-General
       </a>
       at the federal level and by the
       <a href="/wiki/Governors_of_the_Australian_states" title="Governors of the Australian states">
        Governors
       </a>
       at the state level, who by convention act on the advice of her ministers.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Davison_pp287–8_199-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-Davison_pp287–8-199">
         [197]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-200">
        <a href="#cite_note-200">
         [198]
        </a>
       </sup>
       There are two major political groups that usually form government, federally and in the states: the
       <a href="/wiki/Australian_Labor_Party" title="Australian Labor Party">
        Australian Labor Party
       </a>
       and the
       <a href="/wiki/Coalition_(Australia)" title="Coalition (Australia)">
        Coalition
       </a>
       which is a formal grouping of the
       <a href="/wiki/Liberal_Party_of_Australia" title="Liberal Party of Australia">
        Liberal Party
       </a>
       and its minor partner, the
       <a href="/wiki/National_Party_of_Australia" title="National Party of Australia">
        National Party
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-201">
        <a href="#cite_note-201">
         [199]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-202">
        <a href="#cite_note-202">
         [200]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Within Australian political culture, the Coalition is considered
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Centre-right" title="Centre-right">
        centre-right
       </a>
       and the Labor Party is considered
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Centre-left" title="Centre-left">
        centre-left
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-203">
        <a href="#cite_note-203">
         [201]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The
       <a href="/wiki/Australian_Defence_Force" title="Australian Defence Force">
        Australian Defence Force
       </a>
       is by far the largest military force in Oceania.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-204">
        <a href="#cite_note-204">
         [202]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="New_Zealand">
        New Zealand
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=27" title="Edit section: New Zealand">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       Main article:
       <a href="/wiki/Politics_of_New_Zealand" title="Politics of New Zealand">
        Politics of New Zealand
       </a>
      </div>
      <p>
       New Zealand is a
       <a href="/wiki/Constitutional_monarchy" title="Constitutional monarchy">
        constitutional monarchy
       </a>
       with a
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Parliamentary_democracy" title="Parliamentary democracy">
        parliamentary democracy
       </a>
       ,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-GG_constitution_205-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-GG_constitution-205">
         [203]
        </a>
       </sup>
       although
       <a href="/wiki/Constitution_of_New_Zealand" title="Constitution of New Zealand">
        its constitution
       </a>
       is
       <a href="/wiki/Uncodified_constitution" title="Uncodified constitution">
        not codified
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Economist_factsheet_206-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-Economist_factsheet-206">
         [204]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Elizabeth_II" title="Elizabeth II">
        Elizabeth II
       </a>
       is the
       <a href="/wiki/Monarchy_of_New_Zealand" title="Monarchy of New Zealand">
        Queen of New Zealand
       </a>
       and the
       <a href="/wiki/Head_of_state" title="Head of state">
        head of state
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-207">
        <a href="#cite_note-207">
         [205]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The Queen is represented by the
       <a href="/wiki/Governor-General_of_New_Zealand" title="Governor-General of New Zealand">
        Governor-General
       </a>
       , whom she appoints on the
       <a href="/wiki/Advice_(constitutional)" title="Advice (constitutional)">
        advice
       </a>
       of the
       <a href="/wiki/Prime_Minister_of_New_Zealand" title="Prime Minister of New Zealand">
        Prime Minister
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-208">
        <a href="#cite_note-208">
         [206]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The
       <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_Parliament" title="New Zealand Parliament">
        New Zealand Parliament
       </a>
       holds
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Legislative_power" title="Legislative power">
        legislative power
       </a>
       and consists of the Queen and the
       <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_House_of_Representatives" title="New Zealand House of Representatives">
        House of Representatives
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-parliament_facts_209-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-parliament_facts-209">
         [207]
        </a>
       </sup>
       A
       <a href="/wiki/Elections_in_New_Zealand" title="Elections in New Zealand">
        parliamentary general election
       </a>
       must be called no later than three years after the previous election.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-210">
        <a href="#cite_note-210">
         [208]
        </a>
       </sup>
       New Zealand is identified as one of the world's most stable and well-governed states,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-211">
        <a href="#cite_note-211">
         [209]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-212">
        <a href="#cite_note-212">
         [210]
        </a>
       </sup>
       with high government transparency and among the lowest perceived levels of corruption.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-213">
        <a href="#cite_note-213">
         [211]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Pacific_Islands_2">
        Pacific Islands
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=28" title="Edit section: Pacific Islands">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <div class="thumb tleft">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:252px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Samoa_government_building_2010.JPG">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="1093" data-file-width="2048" height="133" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/32/Samoa_government_building_2010.JPG/250px-Samoa_government_building_2010.JPG" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/32/Samoa_government_building_2010.JPG/375px-Samoa_government_building_2010.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/32/Samoa_government_building_2010.JPG/500px-Samoa_government_building_2010.JPG 2x" width="250"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Samoa_government_building_2010.JPG" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         Government building in the capital
         <a href="/wiki/Apia" title="Apia">
          Apia
         </a>
         housing administrative ministerial offices.
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       In
       <a href="/wiki/Politics_of_Samoa" title="Politics of Samoa">
        Samoan politics
       </a>
       , the
       <a href="/wiki/Prime_Minister_of_Samoa" title="Prime Minister of Samoa">
        Prime Minister of Samoa
       </a>
       is the
       <a href="/wiki/Head_of_government" title="Head of government">
        head of government
       </a>
       . The 1960 constitution, which formally came into force with independence from New Zealand in 1962, builds on the British pattern of
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Parliamentary_democracy" title="Parliamentary democracy">
        parliamentary democracy
       </a>
       , modified to take account of Samoan customs. The national government (
       <i>
        malo
       </i>
       ) generally controls the
       <a href="/wiki/Legislative_Assembly_of_Samoa" title="Legislative Assembly of Samoa">
        legislative assembly
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-214">
        <a href="#cite_note-214">
         [212]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Politics_of_Tonga" title="Politics of Tonga">
        Politics of Tonga
       </a>
       takes place in a framework of a constitutional monarchy, whereby the
       <a href="/wiki/King" title="King">
        King
       </a>
       is the Head of State.
      </p>
      <p>
       <a href="/wiki/Politics_of_Fiji" title="Politics of Fiji">
        Fiji
       </a>
       has a multiparty system with the
       <a href="/wiki/Prime_Minister_of_Fiji" title="Prime Minister of Fiji">
        Prime Minister of Fiji
       </a>
       as
       <a href="/wiki/Head_of_government" title="Head of government">
        head of government
       </a>
       . The
       <a href="/wiki/Executive_(government)" title="Executive (government)">
        executive power
       </a>
       is exercised by the government.
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Legislative_power" title="Legislative power">
        Legislative power
       </a>
       is vested in both the government and the
       <a href="/wiki/Parliament_of_Fiji" title="Parliament of Fiji">
        Parliament of Fiji
       </a>
       .
       <a href="/wiki/Fiji" title="Fiji">
        Fiji
       </a>
       's
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Head_of_State_of_Fiji" title="Head of State of Fiji">
        Head of State
       </a>
       is the
       <a href="/wiki/President_of_Fiji" title="President of Fiji">
        President
       </a>
       . He is elected by
       <a href="/wiki/Parliament_of_Fiji" title="Parliament of Fiji">
        Parliament of Fiji
       </a>
       after nomination by the
       <a href="/wiki/Prime_Minister_of_Fiji" title="Prime Minister of Fiji">
        Prime Minister
       </a>
       or the
       <a href="/wiki/Leader_of_the_Opposition_(Fiji)" title="Leader of the Opposition (Fiji)">
        Leader of the Opposition
       </a>
       , for a three-year term.
      </p>
      <p>
       In the
       <a href="/wiki/Politics_of_Papua_New_Guinea" title="Politics of Papua New Guinea">
        politics of Papua New Guinea
       </a>
       the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/List_of_Prime_Ministers_of_the_Papua_New_Guinea" title="List of Prime Ministers of the Papua New Guinea">
        Prime Minister
       </a>
       is the
       <a href="/wiki/Head_of_government" title="Head of government">
        head of government
       </a>
       . In
       <a href="/wiki/Politics_of_Kiribati" title="Politics of Kiribati">
        Kiribati
       </a>
       , the
       <a href="/wiki/President_of_Kiribati" title="President of Kiribati">
        President of Kiribati
       </a>
       is the
       <a href="/wiki/Head_of_government" title="Head of government">
        head of government
       </a>
       , and of a multi-party system.
       <a href="/wiki/Politics_of_New_Caledonia" title="Politics of New Caledonia">
        New Caledonia
       </a>
       remains an integral part of the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/French_Republic" title="French Republic">
        French Republic
       </a>
       . Inhabitants of New Caledonia are
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/French_citizen" title="French citizen">
        French citizens
       </a>
       and carry French passports. They take part in the legislative and presidential French elections. New Caledonia sends two representatives to the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/French_National_Assembly" title="French National Assembly">
        French National Assembly
       </a>
       and two senators to the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/French_Senate" title="French Senate">
        French Senate
       </a>
       .
      </p>
      <p>
       <a href="/wiki/Politics_of_Hawaii" title="Politics of Hawaii">
        Hawaii
       </a>
       is dominated by the
       <a href="/wiki/Democratic_Party_(United_States)" title="Democratic Party (United States)">
        Democratic Party
       </a>
       . As codified in the
       <a href="/wiki/Constitution_of_Hawaii" title="Constitution of Hawaii">
        Constitution of Hawaii
       </a>
       , there are three
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Branches_of_government" title="Branches of government">
        branches of government
       </a>
       : executive, legislative and judicial. The governor is the only state public official elected statewide; all others are appointed by the governor. The lieutenant governor acts as the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Secretary_of_State_of_Hawaii" title="Secretary of State of Hawaii">
        Secretary of State
       </a>
       . The governor and lieutenant governor oversee twenty agencies and departments from offices in the
       <a href="/wiki/Hawaii_State_Capitol" title="Hawaii State Capitol">
        State Capitol
       </a>
       .
      </p>
      <h2>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Culture">
        Culture
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=29" title="Edit section: Culture">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h2>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Australia_3">
        Australia
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=30" title="Edit section: Australia">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       Main articles:
       <a href="/wiki/Culture_of_Australia" title="Culture of Australia">
        Culture of Australia
       </a>
       and
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Cuisine_of_Australia" title="Cuisine of Australia">
        Cuisine of Australia
       </a>
      </div>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Sydney_Opera_House,_botanic_gardens_1.jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="1470" data-file-width="2233" height="145" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/75/Sydney_Opera_House%2C_botanic_gardens_1.jpg/220px-Sydney_Opera_House%2C_botanic_gardens_1.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/75/Sydney_Opera_House%2C_botanic_gardens_1.jpg/330px-Sydney_Opera_House%2C_botanic_gardens_1.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/75/Sydney_Opera_House%2C_botanic_gardens_1.jpg/440px-Sydney_Opera_House%2C_botanic_gardens_1.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Sydney_Opera_House,_botanic_gardens_1.jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         On 28 June 2007, the Sydney Opera House became a
         <a href="/wiki/UNESCO" title="UNESCO">
          UNESCO
         </a>
         <a href="/wiki/World_Heritage_Site" title="World Heritage Site">
          World Heritage Site
         </a>
         .
         <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-215">
          <a href="#cite_note-215">
           [213]
          </a>
         </sup>
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       Since 1788, the primary influence behind Australian culture has been
       <a href="/wiki/Anglo-Celtic" title="Anglo-Celtic">
        Anglo-Celtic
       </a>
       <a href="/wiki/Western_culture" title="Western culture">
        Western culture
       </a>
       , with some
       <a href="/wiki/Indigenous_Australians" title="Indigenous Australians">
        Indigenous
       </a>
       influences.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-216">
        <a href="#cite_note-216">
         [214]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-217">
        <a href="#cite_note-217">
         [215]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The divergence and evolution that has occurred in the ensuing centuries has resulted in a distinctive Australian culture.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Davison_pp98–9_218-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-Davison_pp98–9-218">
         [216]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-219">
        <a href="#cite_note-219">
         [217]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Since the mid-20th century,
       <a href="/wiki/Culture_of_the_United_States" title="Culture of the United States">
        American popular culture
       </a>
       has strongly influenced Australia, particularly through television and cinema.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-tw_220-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-tw-220">
         [218]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Other cultural influences come from neighbouring Asian countries, and through large-scale immigration from non-English-speaking nations.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-tw_220-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-tw-220">
         [218]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-221">
        <a href="#cite_note-221">
         [219]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/The_Story_of_the_Kelly_Gang" title="The Story of the Kelly Gang">
         The Story of the Kelly Gang
        </a>
       </i>
       (1906), the world's first
       <a href="/wiki/Feature_length" title="Feature length">
        feature length
       </a>
       film, spurred a boom in
       <a href="/wiki/Cinema_of_Australia" title="Cinema of Australia">
        Australian cinema
       </a>
       during the
       <a href="/wiki/Silent_film" title="Silent film">
        silent film
       </a>
       era.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-222">
        <a href="#cite_note-222">
         [220]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-223">
        <a href="#cite_note-223">
         [221]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The
       <a href="/wiki/Australian_Museum" title="Australian Museum">
        Australian Museum
       </a>
       in Sydney and the
       <a href="/wiki/National_Gallery_of_Victoria" title="National Gallery of Victoria">
        National Gallery of Victoria
       </a>
       in Melbourne are the oldest and
       <a href="/wiki/List_of_largest_art_museums" title="List of largest art museums">
        largest
       </a>
       <a href="/wiki/Museum" title="Museum">
        museums
       </a>
       in Oceania.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-224">
        <a href="#cite_note-224">
         [222]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-VHR_225-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-VHR-225">
         [223]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The city's
       <a href="/wiki/Sydney_New_Year%27s_Eve" title="Sydney New Year's Eve">
        New Year's Eve
       </a>
       celebrations are the largest in Oceania.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-226">
        <a href="#cite_note-226">
         [224]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       Australia is also known for its
       <a href="/wiki/Coffeehouse" title="Coffeehouse">
        cafe
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Coffee_culture" title="Coffee culture">
        coffee culture
       </a>
       in
       <a href="/wiki/Urban_area" title="Urban area">
        urban centres
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-227">
        <a href="#cite_note-227">
         [225]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Australia and
       <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand" title="New Zealand">
        New Zealand
       </a>
       were responsible for the
       <a href="/wiki/Flat_white" title="Flat white">
        flat white
       </a>
       coffee. Most Indigenous Australian tribal groups subsisted on a simple
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Hunter-gatherer_diet" title="Hunter-gatherer diet">
        hunter-gatherer diet
       </a>
       of native fauna and flora, otherwise called
       <a href="/wiki/Bush_tucker" title="Bush tucker">
        bush tucker
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-228">
        <a href="#cite_note-228">
         [226]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-229">
        <a href="#cite_note-229">
         [227]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The first settlers introduced
       <a href="/wiki/British_cuisine" title="British cuisine">
        British food
       </a>
       to the continent, much of which is now considered typical Australian food, such as the
       <a href="/wiki/Sunday_roast" title="Sunday roast">
        Sunday roast
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-food_230-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-food-230">
         [228]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-f2_231-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-f2-231">
         [229]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Multicultural immigration transformed Australian cuisine; post-World War II European migrants, particularly from the Mediterranean, helped to build a thriving Australian
       <a href="/wiki/Coffee_culture" title="Coffee culture">
        coffee culture
       </a>
       , and the influence of
       <a href="/wiki/Culture_of_Asia" title="Culture of Asia">
        Asian cultures
       </a>
       has led to Australian variants of their staple foods, such as the
       <a href="/wiki/Chinese_cuisine" title="Chinese cuisine">
        Chinese
       </a>
       -inspired
       <a href="/wiki/Dim_sim" title="Dim sim">
        dim sim
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Chiko_Roll" title="Chiko Roll">
        Chiko Roll
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-232">
        <a href="#cite_note-232">
         [230]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Iolani_Palace_(1328).JPG">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="743" data-file-width="967" height="169" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/Iolani_Palace_%281328%29.JPG/220px-Iolani_Palace_%281328%29.JPG" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/Iolani_Palace_%281328%29.JPG/330px-Iolani_Palace_%281328%29.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/Iolani_Palace_%281328%29.JPG/440px-Iolani_Palace_%281328%29.JPG 2x" width="220"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Iolani_Palace_(1328).JPG" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         The
         <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Iolani_Palace" title="Iolani Palace">
          <span class="unicode">
           ʻ
          </span>
          Iolani Palace
         </a>
         in
         <a href="/wiki/Honolulu" title="Honolulu">
          Honolulu
         </a>
         , formerly the residence of the Hawaiian monarch, was restored and opened to the public as a
         <a href="/wiki/Museum" title="Museum">
          museum
         </a>
         in 1978.
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Hawaii">
        Hawaii
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=31" title="Edit section: Hawaii">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       Main articles:
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Culture_of_Hawaii" title="Culture of Hawaii">
        Culture of Hawaii
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Cuisine_of_Hawaii" title="Cuisine of Hawaii">
        Cuisine of Hawaii
       </a>
       , and
       <a href="/wiki/Hawaiian_religion" title="Hawaiian religion">
        Hawaiian religion
       </a>
      </div>
      <p>
       The music of Hawaii includes traditional and popular styles, ranging from native Hawaiian folk music to modern
       <a href="/wiki/Rock_music" title="Rock music">
        rock
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Hip_hop_music" title="Hip hop music">
        hip hop
       </a>
       . Hawaii's musical contributions to the
       <a href="/wiki/Music_of_the_United_States" title="Music of the United States">
        music of the United States
       </a>
       are out of proportion to the state's small size. Styles such as
       <a href="/wiki/Slack-key_guitar" title="Slack-key guitar">
        slack-key guitar
       </a>
       are well-known worldwide, while Hawaiian-tinged music is a frequent part of
       <a href="/wiki/Cinema_of_the_United_States" title="Cinema of the United States">
        Hollywood
       </a>
       soundtracks. Hawaii also made a major contribution to
       <a href="/wiki/Country_music" title="Country music">
        country music
       </a>
       with the introduction of the
       <a href="/wiki/Steel_guitar" title="Steel guitar">
        steel guitar
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Unterberger_233-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-Unterberger-233">
         [231]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The Hawaiian religion is
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Polytheistic" title="Polytheistic">
        polytheistic
       </a>
       and
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Animistic" title="Animistic">
        animistic
       </a>
       , with a belief in many deities and spirits, including the belief that spirits are found in non-human beings and objects such as animals, the waves, and the sky.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Chai_234-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-Chai-234">
         [232]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       The
       <a href="/wiki/Cuisine_of_Hawaii" title="Cuisine of Hawaii">
        cuisine of Hawaii
       </a>
       is a fusion of many foods brought by immigrants to the Hawaiian Islands, including the earliest Polynesians and
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Native_Hawaiian_cuisine" title="Native Hawaiian cuisine">
        Native Hawaiian cuisine
       </a>
       , and
       <a href="/wiki/Cuisine_of_the_United_States" title="Cuisine of the United States">
        American
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Chinese_cuisine" title="Chinese cuisine">
        Chinese
       </a>
       ,
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Philippine_cuisine" title="Philippine cuisine">
        Filipino
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Japanese_cuisine" title="Japanese cuisine">
        Japanese
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Korean_cuisine" title="Korean cuisine">
        Korean
       </a>
       ,
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Polynesian_cuisine" title="Polynesian cuisine">
        Polynesian
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Portuguese_cuisine" title="Portuguese cuisine">
        Portuguese
       </a>
       origins. Native Hawaiian musician and Hawaiian sovereignty activist
       <a href="/wiki/Israel_Kamakawiwo%CA%BBole" title="Israel Kamakawiwoʻole">
        Israel Kamakawiwoʻole
       </a>
       , famous for his medley of "
       <a href="/wiki/Somewhere_Over_the_Rainbow/What_a_Wonderful_World" title="Somewhere Over the Rainbow/What a Wonderful World">
        Somewhere Over the Rainbow/What a Wonderful World
       </a>
       ", was named "The Voice of Hawaii" by
       <a href="/wiki/NPR" title="NPR">
        NPR
       </a>
       in 2010 in its 50 great voices series.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-235">
        <a href="#cite_note-235">
         [233]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="New_Zealand_2">
        New Zealand
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=32" title="Edit section: New Zealand">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       Main articles:
       <a href="/wiki/Culture_of_New_Zealand" title="Culture of New Zealand">
        Culture of New Zealand
       </a>
       and
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Cuisine_of_New_Zealand" title="Cuisine of New Zealand">
        Cuisine of New Zealand
       </a>
      </div>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Hobbit_holes_reflected_in_water.jpg">
         <img alt="Hills with inset, round doors. Reflected in water." class="thumbimage" data-file-height="3456" data-file-width="5184" height="147" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/Hobbit_holes_reflected_in_water.jpg/220px-Hobbit_holes_reflected_in_water.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/Hobbit_holes_reflected_in_water.jpg/330px-Hobbit_holes_reflected_in_water.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/Hobbit_holes_reflected_in_water.jpg/440px-Hobbit_holes_reflected_in_water.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Hobbit_holes_reflected_in_water.jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         The
         <a href="/wiki/Hobbiton_Movie_Set" title="Hobbiton Movie Set">
          Hobbiton Movie Set
         </a>
         , located near
         <a href="/wiki/Matamata" title="Matamata">
          Matamata
         </a>
         , was used for
         <i>
          The Lord of the Rings
         </i>
         film trilogy.
         <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-236">
          <a href="#cite_note-236">
           [234]
          </a>
         </sup>
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       New Zealand as a culture is a Western culture, which is influenced by the cultural input of the indigenous
       <a href="/wiki/M%C4%81ori_people" title="Māori people">
        Māori
       </a>
       and the various waves of multi-ethnic migration which followed the
       <a href="/wiki/History_of_New_Zealand" title="History of New Zealand">
        British colonisation of New Zealand
       </a>
       . Māori people constitute one of the major cultures of Polynesia. The country has been broadened by globalisation and immigration from the
       <a href="/wiki/Pacific_Islands" title="Pacific Islands">
        Pacific Islands
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/East_Asia" title="East Asia">
        East Asia
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/South_Asia" title="South Asia">
        South Asia
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-237">
        <a href="#cite_note-237">
         [235]
        </a>
       </sup>
       New Zealand marks two national days of remembrance,
       <a href="/wiki/Waitangi_Day" title="Waitangi Day">
        Waitangi Day
       </a>
       and
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/ANZAC_Day" title="ANZAC Day">
        ANZAC Day
       </a>
       , and also celebrates holidays during or close to the anniversaries of the founding dates of each province.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-238">
        <a href="#cite_note-238">
         [236]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       The New Zealand recording industry began to develop from 1940 onwards and many New Zealand musicians have obtained success in Britain and the United States.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-music_239-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-music-239">
         [237]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Some artists release Māori language songs and the Māori tradition-based art of
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Kapa_haka" title="Kapa haka">
         kapa haka
        </a>
       </i>
       (song and dance) has made a resurgence.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-240">
        <a href="#cite_note-240">
         [238]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The country's diverse scenery and compact size, plus government incentives,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-241">
        <a href="#cite_note-241">
         [239]
        </a>
       </sup>
       have encouraged some
       <a href="/wiki/Film_producer" title="Film producer">
        producers
       </a>
       to film big budget movies in New Zealand, including
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Avatar_(2009_film)" title="Avatar (2009 film)">
         Avatar
        </a>
       </i>
       ,
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings_(film_series)" title="The Lord of the Rings (film series)">
         The Lord of the Rings
        </a>
       </i>
       ,
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/The_Hobbit_(film_series)" title="The Hobbit (film series)">
         The Hobbit
        </a>
       </i>
       ,
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/The_Chronicles_of_Narnia_(film_series)" title="The Chronicles of Narnia (film series)">
         The Chronicles of Narnia
        </a>
       </i>
       ,
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/King_Kong_(2005_film)" title="King Kong (2005 film)">
         King Kong
        </a>
       </i>
       and
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/The_Last_Samurai" title="The Last Samurai">
         The Last Samurai
        </a>
       </i>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-242">
        <a href="#cite_note-242">
         [240]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       The national cuisine has been described as
       <a href="/wiki/Pacific_Rim" title="Pacific Rim">
        Pacific Rim
       </a>
       , incorporating the native
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/M%C4%81ori_cuisine" title="Māori cuisine">
        Māori cuisine
       </a>
       and diverse culinary traditions introduced by settlers and immigrants from Europe, Polynesia and Asia.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-cuisine_243-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-cuisine-243">
         [241]
        </a>
       </sup>
       New Zealand yields produce from land and sea—most crops and livestock, such as maize, potatoes and pigs, were gradually introduced by the early European settlers.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-244">
        <a href="#cite_note-244">
         [242]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Distinctive ingredients or dishes include
       <a href="/wiki/Lamb_and_mutton" title="Lamb and mutton">
        lamb
       </a>
       , salmon,
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/K%C5%8Dura" title="Kōura">
        kōura
       </a>
       (crayfish),
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-245">
        <a href="#cite_note-245">
         [243]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Dredge_oyster" title="Dredge oyster">
        dredge oysters
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Whitebait" title="Whitebait">
        whitebait
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/P%C4%81ua" title="Pāua">
        pāua
       </a>
       (abalone), mussels, scallops,
       <a href="/wiki/Paphies_australis" title="Paphies australis">
        pipis
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Tuatua" title="Tuatua">
        tuatua
       </a>
       (both are types of New Zealand shellfish),
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-246">
        <a href="#cite_note-246">
         [244]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/K%C5%ABmara" title="Kūmara">
        kūmara
       </a>
       (sweet potato),
       <a href="/wiki/Kiwifruit" title="Kiwifruit">
        kiwifruit
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Tamarillo" title="Tamarillo">
        tamarillo
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Pavlova_(food)" title="Pavlova (food)">
        pavlova
       </a>
       (considered a national dish).
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-247">
        <a href="#cite_note-247">
         [245]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-cuisine_243-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-cuisine-243">
         [241]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Samoa">
        Samoa
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=33" title="Edit section: Samoa">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Fale_on_Manono_Island.jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="683" data-file-width="1024" height="147" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f2/Fale_on_Manono_Island.jpg/220px-Fale_on_Manono_Island.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f2/Fale_on_Manono_Island.jpg/330px-Fale_on_Manono_Island.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f2/Fale_on_Manono_Island.jpg/440px-Fale_on_Manono_Island.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
