         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Fale_on_Manono_Island.jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         A
         <a href="/wiki/Architecture_of_Samoa" title="Architecture of Samoa">
          fale
         </a>
         on
         <a href="/wiki/Manono_Island" title="Manono Island">
          Manono Island
         </a>
         .
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       Main articles:
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Culture_of_Samoa" title="Culture of Samoa">
        Culture of Samoa
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Polynesian_culture" title="Polynesian culture">
        Polynesian culture
       </a>
      </div>
      <p>
       The
       <a href="/wiki/Fa%27a_Samoa" title="Fa'a Samoa">
        fa'a Samoa
       </a>
       , or traditional Samoan way, remains a strong force in Samoan life and politics. Despite centuries of European influence, Samoa maintains its historical customs, social and political systems, and
       <a href="/wiki/Samoan_language" title="Samoan language">
        language
       </a>
       . Cultural customs such as the
       <a href="/wiki/Samoa_%27ava_ceremony" title="Samoa 'ava ceremony">
        Samoa 'ava ceremony
       </a>
       are significant and solemn rituals at important occasions including the bestowal of
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Fa%27amatai" title="Fa'amatai">
         matai
        </a>
       </i>
       chiefly titles. Items of great cultural value include the finely woven
       <i>
        <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/%27ie_toga" title="'ie toga">
         'ie toga
        </a>
       </i>
       .
      </p>
      <p>
       The Samoan word for dance is
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Siva_Samoa" title="Siva Samoa">
         siva
        </a>
       </i>
       with unique gentle movements of the body in time to music and which tell a story, although the Samoan male dances can be more snappy.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-248">
        <a href="#cite_note-248">
         [246]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Sasa_(dance)" title="Sasa (dance)">
         sasa
        </a>
       </i>
       is also a traditional dance where rows of dancers perform rapid
       <a href="/wiki/Synchronization" title="Synchronization">
        synchronised
       </a>
       movements in time to the rhythm of wooden drums
       <i>
        (
        <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Pate_(musical_instrument)" title="Pate (musical instrument)">
         pate
        </a>
        )
       </i>
       or rolled mats. Another dance performed by males is called the
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Fa%27ataupati" title="Fa'ataupati">
         fa'ataupati
        </a>
       </i>
       or the slap dance, creating rhythmic sounds by slapping different parts of the body. As with other Polynesian cultures (
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Hawaiian_culture" title="Hawaiian culture">
        Hawaiian
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Tahitians" title="Tahitians">
        Tahitian
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/M%C4%81ori_culture" title="Māori culture">
        Māori
       </a>
       ) with significant and unique tattoos, Samoans have two gender specific and culturally significant tattoos.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-249">
        <a href="#cite_note-249">
         [247]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Arts">
        Arts
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=34" title="Edit section: Arts">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       Main articles:
       <a href="/wiki/Oceanian_art" title="Oceanian art">
        Oceanian art
       </a>
       ,
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Samoan_art" title="Samoan art">
        Samoan art
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Hawaiian_art" title="Hawaiian art">
        Hawaiian art
       </a>
       ,
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Maori_art" title="Maori art">
        Maori art
       </a>
       , and
       <a href="/wiki/Indigenous_Australian_art" title="Indigenous Australian art">
        Indigenous Australian art
       </a>
      </div>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:232px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Bradshaw_rock_paintings.jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="683" data-file-width="1024" height="153" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/43/Bradshaw_rock_paintings.jpg/230px-Bradshaw_rock_paintings.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/43/Bradshaw_rock_paintings.jpg/345px-Bradshaw_rock_paintings.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/43/Bradshaw_rock_paintings.jpg/460px-Bradshaw_rock_paintings.jpg 2x" width="230"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Bradshaw_rock_paintings.jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         <a href="/wiki/Bradshaw_rock_paintings" title="Bradshaw rock paintings">
          Bradshaw rock paintings
         </a>
         found in the north-west
         <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Kimberley_region_of_Western_Australia" title="Kimberley region of Western Australia">
          Kimberley region of Western Australia
         </a>
         .
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       The artistic creations of native Oceanians varies greatly throughout the cultures and regions. The subject matter typically carries themes of fertility or the supernatural.
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Petroglyphs" title="Petroglyphs">
        Petroglyphs
       </a>
       ,
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Tattooing" title="Tattooing">
        Tattooing
       </a>
       , painting, wood carving, stone carving and textile work are other common art forms.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-250">
        <a href="#cite_note-250">
         [248]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Art of Oceania properly encompasses the artistic traditions of the people indigenous to Australia and the
       <a href="/wiki/Pacific_Islands" title="Pacific Islands">
        Pacific Islands
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-oce_251-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-oce-251">
         [249]
        </a>
       </sup>
       These early peoples lacked a
       <a href="/wiki/Writing_system" title="Writing system">
        writing system
       </a>
       , and made works on perishable materials, so few records of them exist from this time.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-252">
        <a href="#cite_note-252">
         [250]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       Indigenous Australian
       <a href="/wiki/Rock_art" title="Rock art">
        rock art
       </a>
       is the oldest and richest unbroken tradition of art in the world, dating as far back as 60,000 years and spread across hundreds of thousands of sites.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-253">
        <a href="#cite_note-253">
         [251]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-254">
        <a href="#cite_note-254">
         [252]
        </a>
       </sup>
       These rock paintings served several functions. Some were used in magic, others to increase animal populations for hunting, while some were simply for amusement.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-255">
        <a href="#cite_note-255">
         [253]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Sculpture in Oceania first appears on New Guinea as a series of stone figures found throughout the island, but mostly in mountainous highlands. Establishing a chronological timeframe for these pieces in most cases is difficult, but one has been dated to 1500 BC.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-256">
        <a href="#cite_note-256">
         [254]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       By 1500 BC the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Lapita" title="Lapita">
        Lapita
       </a>
       culture, descendants of the second wave, would begin to expand and spread into the more remote islands. At around the same time, art began to appear in New Guinea, including the earliest examples of sculpture in Oceania. Starting around 1100 AD, the people of Easter Island would begin construction of nearly 900
       <a href="/wiki/Moai" title="Moai">
        moai
       </a>
       (large stone statues). At about 1200 AD, the people of Pohnpei, a Micronesian island, would embark on another megalithic construction, building
       <a href="/wiki/Nan_Madol" title="Nan Madol">
        Nan Madol
       </a>
       , a city of artificial islands and a system of canals.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-257">
        <a href="#cite_note-257">
         [255]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Hawaiian art includes
       <a href="/wiki/Wood_carving" title="Wood carving">
        wood carvings
       </a>
       , feather work, petroglyphs, bark cloth (called
       <a href="/wiki/Kapa" title="Kapa">
        kapa
       </a>
       in Hawaiian and
       <a href="/wiki/Tapa_cloth" title="Tapa cloth">
        tapa
       </a>
       elsewhere in the Pacific) and tattoos. Native Hawaiians had neither
       <a href="/wiki/Metal" title="Metal">
        metal
       </a>
       nor woven cloth.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-258">
        <a href="#cite_note-258">
         [256]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Sport">
        Sport
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=35" title="Edit section: Sport">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       See also:
       <a href="/wiki/Sport_in_Oceania" title="Sport in Oceania">
        Sport in Oceania
       </a>
      </div>
      <div class="thumb tleft">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Fiji_vs_Wales_CG_Melbourne_2006.jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="1536" data-file-width="2048" height="165" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/56/Fiji_vs_Wales_CG_Melbourne_2006.jpg/220px-Fiji_vs_Wales_CG_Melbourne_2006.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/56/Fiji_vs_Wales_CG_Melbourne_2006.jpg/330px-Fiji_vs_Wales_CG_Melbourne_2006.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/56/Fiji_vs_Wales_CG_Melbourne_2006.jpg/440px-Fiji_vs_Wales_CG_Melbourne_2006.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Fiji_vs_Wales_CG_Melbourne_2006.jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         Fiji playing
         <a href="/wiki/Wales_national_rugby_sevens_team" title="Wales national rugby sevens team">
          Wales
         </a>
         at
         <a href="/wiki/Rugby_sevens" title="Rugby sevens">
          seven-a-side rugby
         </a>
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       <a href="/wiki/Rugby_union" title="Rugby union">
        Rugby union
       </a>
       is one of the region's most prominent sports,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-259">
        <a href="#cite_note-259">
         [257]
        </a>
       </sup>
       and is the national sport of New Zealand, Samoa, Fiji and Tonga. The most popular sport in Australia is
       <a href="/wiki/Cricket" title="Cricket">
        cricket
       </a>
       , the most popular sport among Australian women is
       <a href="/wiki/Netball" title="Netball">
        netball
       </a>
       , while
       <a href="/wiki/Australian_rules_football" title="Australian rules football">
        Australian rules football
       </a>
       is the most popular sport in terms of spectatorship and television ratings.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-260">
        <a href="#cite_note-260">
         [258]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-261">
        <a href="#cite_note-261">
         [259]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-262">
        <a href="#cite_note-262">
         [260]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Rugby is the most popular sport among New Zealanders.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-263">
        <a href="#cite_note-263">
         [261]
        </a>
       </sup>
       In Papua New Guinea, the most popular sport is the
       <a href="/wiki/Rugby_league" title="Rugby league">
        Rugby league
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-rl_264-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-rl-264">
         [262]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       <a href="/wiki/Australian_rules_football" title="Australian rules football">
        Australian rules football
       </a>
       is the national sport in Nauru
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-265">
        <a href="#cite_note-265">
         [263]
        </a>
       </sup>
       and is the most popular football code in Australia in terms of attendance.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-266">
        <a href="#cite_note-266">
         [264]
        </a>
       </sup>
       It has a large following in Papua New Guinea, where it is the second most popular sport after Rugby League.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-267">
        <a href="#cite_note-267">
         [265]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-268">
        <a href="#cite_note-268">
         [266]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-269">
        <a href="#cite_note-269">
         [267]
        </a>
       </sup>
       It attracts significant attention across New Zealand and the
       <a href="/wiki/Pacific_Islands" title="Pacific Islands">
        Pacific Islands
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-270">
        <a href="#cite_note-270">
         [268]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Fiji_national_rugby_sevens_team" title="Fiji national rugby sevens team">
        Fiji's sevens team
       </a>
       is one of the most successful in the world, as is
       <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_national_rugby_sevens_team" title="New Zealand national rugby sevens team">
        New Zealand's
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-271">
        <a href="#cite_note-271">
         [269]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       Currently,
       <a href="/wiki/Vanuatu" title="Vanuatu">
        Vanuatu
       </a>
       is the only country in Oceania to call
       <a href="/wiki/Association_football" title="Association football">
        association football
       </a>
       its national sport. However, it is also the most popular sport in
       <a href="/wiki/Kiribati" title="Kiribati">
        Kiribati
       </a>
       , the
       <a href="/wiki/Solomon_Islands" title="Solomon Islands">
        Solomon Islands
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Tuvalu" title="Tuvalu">
        Tuvalu
       </a>
       , and has a significant (and growing) popularity in
       <a href="/wiki/Soccer_in_Australia" title="Soccer in Australia">
        Australia
       </a>
       . In 2006,
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Socceroo" title="Socceroo">
        Australia
       </a>
       joined the
       <a href="/wiki/Asian_Football_Confederation" title="Asian Football Confederation">
        Asian Football Confederation
       </a>
       and qualified for the 2010 and
       <a href="/wiki/2014_FIFA_World_Cup" title="2014 FIFA World Cup">
        2014
       </a>
       World Cups as an Asian entrant.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-272">
        <a href="#cite_note-272">
         [270]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       Australia has hosted two Summer Olympics:
       <a href="/wiki/1956_Summer_Olympics" title="1956 Summer Olympics">
        Melbourne 1956
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/2000_Summer_Olympics" title="2000 Summer Olympics">
        Sydney 2000
       </a>
       . Also, Australia has hosted four editions of the
       <a href="/wiki/Commonwealth_Games" title="Commonwealth Games">
        Commonwealth Games
       </a>
       (
       <a href="/wiki/1938_British_Empire_Games" title="1938 British Empire Games">
        Sydney 1938
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/1962_British_Empire_and_Commonwealth_Games" title="1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games">
        Perth 1962
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/1982_Commonwealth_Games" title="1982 Commonwealth Games">
        Brisbane 1982
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/2006_Commonwealth_Games" title="2006 Commonwealth Games">
        Melbourne 2006
       </a>
       ), and is scheduled for a fifth (
       <a href="/wiki/2018_Commonwealth_Games" title="2018 Commonwealth Games">
        Gold Coast 2018
       </a>
       ). Meanwhile, New Zealand has hosted the Commonwealth Games three times:
       <a href="/wiki/1950_British_Empire_Games" title="1950 British Empire Games">
        Auckland 1950
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/1974_British_Commonwealth_Games" title="1974 British Commonwealth Games">
        Christchurch 1974
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/1990_Commonwealth_Games" title="1990 Commonwealth Games">
        Auckland 1990
       </a>
       . The
       <a href="/wiki/Pacific_Games" title="Pacific Games">
        Pacific Games
       </a>
       (formerly known as the South Pacific Games) is a multi-sport event, much like the Olympics on a much smaller scale, with participation exclusively from countries around the Pacific. It is held every four years and began in 1963. Australia and New Zealand competed in the games for the first time in 2015.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-273">
        <a href="#cite_note-273">
         [271]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>

        <li id="cite_note-Lewis_1997_32-21">
         <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
          <b>
           <a href="#cite_ref-Lewis_1997_32_21-0">
            ^
           </a>
          </b>
         </span>
         <span class="reference-text">
          <cite class="citation book">
           Lewis, Martin W.; Kären E. Wigen (1997).
           <i>
            The Myth of Continents: a Critique of Metageography
           </i>
           . Berkeley: University of California Press. p. 32.
           <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">
            ISBN
           </a>
           <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-520-20742-4" title="Special:BookSources/0-520-20742-4">
            0-520-20742-4
           </a>
           .
           <q>
            Interestingly enough, the answer [from a scholar who sought to calculate the number of continents] conformed almost precisely to the conventional list: North America, South America, Europe, Asia, Oceania (Australia plus New Zealand), Africa, and Antarctica.
           </q>

        <li id="cite_note-burley128-38">
         <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
          <b>
           <a href="#cite_ref-burley128_38-0">
            ^
           </a>
          </b>
         </span>
         <span class="reference-text">
          <cite class="citation journal">
           Burley, David V.; Barton, Andrew; Dickinson, William R.; Connaughton, Sean P.; Taché, Karine (2010). "Nukuleka as a Founder Colony for West Polynesian Settlement: New Insights from Recent Excavations".
           <i>
            Journal of Pacific Archaeology
           </i>
           .
           <b>
            1
           </b>
           (2): 128–144.
          </cite>
          <span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Journal+of+Pacific+Archaeology&amp;rft.atitle=Nukuleka+as+a+Founder+Colony+for+West+Polynesian+Settlement%3A+New+Insights+from+Recent+Excavations&amp;rft.volume=1&amp;rft.issue=2&amp;rft.pages=128-144&amp;rft.date=2010&amp;rft.aulast=Burley&amp;rft.aufirst=David+V.&amp;rft.au=Barton%2C+Andrew&amp;rft.au=Dickinson%2C+William+R.&amp;rft.au=Connaughton%2C+Sean+P.&amp;rft.au=Tach%C3%A9%2C+Karine&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AOceania">
           <span style="display:none;">
           </span>
          </span>
         </span>
        </li>
        <li id="cite_note-39">
         <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
          <b>
           <a href="#cite_ref-39">
            ^
           </a>
          </b>
         </span>
         <span class="reference-text">
          Resemblance of the name to an early
          <a href="/wiki/Mangareva" title="Mangareva">
           Mangarevan
          </a>
          founder god
          <i>
           <a class="new" href="/w/index.php?title=Atu_Motua&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" title="Atu Motua (page does not exist)">
            Atu Motua
           </a>
          </i>
          ("Father Lord") has made some historians suspect that Hotu Matua was added to Easter Island mythology only in the 1860s, along with adopting the Mangarevan language. The "real" founder would have been
          <i>
           <a class="new" href="/w/index.php?title=Tu%27u_ko_Iho&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" title="Tu'u ko Iho (page does not exist)">
            Tu'u ko Iho
           </a>
          </i>
          , who became just a supporting character in Hotu Matu'a centric legends. See Steven Fischer (1994).
          <i>
           Rapanui's Tu'u ko Iho Versus Mangareva's 'Atu Motua. Evidence for Multiple Reanalysis and Replacement in Rapanui Settlement Traditions, Easter Island.
          </i>
          The Journal of Pacific History, 29(1), 3–18. See also
          <i>
           Rapa Nui / Geography, History and Religion
          </i>
          . Peter H. Buck, Vikings of the Pacific, University of Chicago Press, 1938. pp. 228–236.
          <a class="external text" href="http://pvs.kcc.hawaii.edu/rapanui/rapa1.html" rel="nofollow">
           Online version
          </a>
          .
         </span>
        </li>
        <li id="cite_note-40">
         <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
          <b>
           <a href="#cite_ref-40">
            ^
           </a>
          </b>
         </span>
         <span class="reference-text">
          <a class="external text" href="http://pvs.kcc.hawaii.edu/rapanui/hotu.html" rel="nofollow">
           Summary of Thomas S. Barthel's version of Hotu Matu'a's arrival to Easter Island
          </a>
          .
         </span>
        </li>
        <li id="cite_note-41">
         <span class="mw-cite-backlink">

           <a href="#cite_ref-41">

         <span class="reference-text">

          <span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Papuan+province+changes+name+from+West+Irian+Jaya+to+West+Papua&amp;rft.pub=Radio+New+Zealand+International&amp;rft.date=2007-02-07&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.rnzi.com%2Fpages%2Fnews.php%3Fop%3Dread%26id%3D29965&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AOceania">
           <span style="display:none;">
           </span>
          </span>
         </span>
        </li>
        <li id="cite_note-pngaus-140">
         <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
          <b>
           <a href="#cite_ref-pngaus_140-0">
            ^
           </a>
          </b>
         </span>
         <span class="reference-text">
          <a href="/wiki/Papua_New_Guinea" title="Papua New Guinea">
           Papua New Guinea
          </a>
          is often considered part of
          <a href="/wiki/Australasia" title="Australasia">
           Australasia
          </a>
          and
          <a href="/wiki/Melanesia" title="Melanesia">
           Melanesia
          </a>
          . It is sometimes included in the
          <a href="/wiki/Malay_Archipelago" title="Malay Archipelago">
           Malay Archipelago
          </a>
          of
          <a href="/wiki/Southeast_Asia" title="Southeast Asia">
           Southeast Asia
          </a>
          .
          <br/>
         </span>
        </li>
        <li id="cite_note-Palau-141">
         <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
          <b>
           <a href="#cite_ref-Palau_141-0">
            ^
           </a>
          </b>
         </span>
         <span class="reference-text">
          On 7 October 2006, government officials moved their offices in the former capital of
          <a href="/wiki/Koror" title="Koror">
           Koror
          </a>
          to
          <a href="/wiki/Ngerulmud" title="Ngerulmud">
           Ngerulmud
          </a>
          in the state of
          <a href="/wiki/Melekeok" title="Melekeok">
           Melekeok
          </a>
          , located 20 km (12 mi) northeast of Koror on
          <a href="/wiki/Babeldaob" title="Babeldaob">
           Babelthuap Island
          </a>
          .
          <br/>
         </span>
        </li>
        <li id="cite_note-ASamoa-142">
         <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
          <b>
           <a href="#cite_ref-ASamoa_142-0">
            ^
           </a>
          </b>
         </span>
         <span class="reference-text">
          <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Fagatogo,_American_Samoa" title="Fagatogo, American Samoa">
           Fagatogo
          </a>
          is the seat of government of
          <a href="/wiki/American_Samoa" title="American Samoa">
           American Samoa
          </a>
          .
          <br/>
         </span>
        </li>

           Wilson, Andy (2009-11-05).
           <a class="external text" href="https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2009/nov/05/england-rugby-league-australia-new-zealand" rel="nofollow">

      <h2>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Further_reading">
        Further reading
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=Oceania&amp;action=edit&amp;section=38" title="Edit section: Further reading">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h2>
      <ul>
       <li>
        <a href="/wiki/Frank_Harary" title="Frank Harary">
         Frank Harary
        </a>
        &amp; Per Hage (1991)
        <i>
         Exchange in Oceania: A Graph Theoretic Analysis
        </i>
        , Oxford Studies in Social and Cultural Anthropology,
        <a href="/wiki/Oxford_University_Press" title="Oxford University Press">
         Oxford University Press
        </a>
        .
       </li>
       <li>
        Frank Harary &amp; Per Hage (2007)
        <i>
         Island Networks: Communication, Kinship, and Classification Structures in Oceania
        </i>
        , Structural Analysis in the Social Sciences,
        <a href="/wiki/Cambridge_University_Press" title="Cambridge University Press">
         Cambridge University Press
        </a>
        .
       </li>
      </ul>
